\begin_layout Section
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gibbs-Duhem Equation
\end_layout

\end_inset

A Most Useful Equation: The Generalized Gibbs-Duhem Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$X_A, X_B$"
description "Mole fractions of A and B"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\mu_A, \\mu_B$"
description "chemical potentials of A and B"

\end_inset

From our knowledge of thermodynamics, most of us are familiar with the standard
 form of the 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gibbs-Duhem equation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gibbs-Duhem equation
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Binary Gibbs-Duhem"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=X_{A}d\mu_{A}+X_{B}d\mu_{B}\label{eq:Binary Gibbs-Duhem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is used extensively to describe the behavior of solutions, namely,
 it plays a big role in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solution thermodynamics.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This equation only holds true for binary systems at fixed temperature and
 pressure, the X terms represent mole fractions, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 terms represent chemical potentials.
 A more general form of the Gibbs-Duhem equation can be derived as follows.
 Let's start with a binary system.
 The total internal energy (U) is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:total U"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=TS-PV+n_{1}\mu_{1}+n_{2}\mu_{2}\label{eq:total U}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is absolute temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is pressure, the n terms represent the number of moles of each component,
 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 terms are chemical potentials, as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Binary Gibbs-Duhem"

\end_inset

.
 However, from the 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First law of thermodynamics
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
First law of thermodynamics
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:first law"

\end_inset

) we know that the change of internal energy is a balance between heat 
\emph on
in
\emph default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q$
\end_inset

) and work done 
\emph on
by
\emph default
 (or out of) our system (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta w$
\end_inset

).
 For now and for the sake of simplicity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta w$
\end_inset

 will be limited to 
\begin_inset Formula $PV$
\end_inset

-work only (at constant pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta w$
\end_inset

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $PdV$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dU=\delta q-\delta w=\delta q-PdV\label{eq:first law}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second law of thermodynamics (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2nd law"

\end_inset

) tells us that the change of the entropy (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) of the system is always greater than the actual heat in (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q$
\end_inset

) divided by absolute temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dS\geq\delta q/T\label{eq:2nd law}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact, the entropy change is equal to the reversible heat in (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q_{rev}$
\end_inset

) divided by absolute temperature, as expressed in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2nd law reversible"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dS=\delta q_{rev}/T\label{eq:2nd law reversible}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we now combine the first law (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:first law"

\end_inset

) and the second law (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2nd law"

\end_inset

) for a closed system (no matter in or out, i.e., no 
\begin_inset Formula $nd\mu$
\end_inset

 terms), we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:combo1st2nd"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dU\leq TdS-PdV\label{eq:combo1st2nd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or at equilibrium, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta q_{rev}$
\end_inset

, and equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2nd law reversible"

\end_inset

 instead of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2nd law"

\end_inset

, we get equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1st2ndequilibrium"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dU=TdS-PdV\label{eq:1st2ndequilibrium}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's consider an open system that can exchange matter with the environment.
 We will keep it a binary system for now (and for the sake of simplicity).
 With the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu dn$
\end_inset

 terms added, the combined first and second law equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1st2ndequilibrium"

\end_inset

 becomes equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:comboBin1st2nd"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dU=TdS-PdV+\mu_{1}dn_{1}+\mu_{2}dn_{2}\label{eq:comboBin1st2nd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the total differential of total internal energy, equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:total U"

\end_inset

, gives us equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Utotaldiff"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dU=TdS+SdT-PdV-VdP+n_{1}d\mu_{1}+\mu_{1}dn_{1}+n_{2}d\mu_{2}+\mu_{2}dn_{2}\label{eq:Utotaldiff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we now subtract equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:comboBin1st2nd"

\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Utotaldiff"

\end_inset

, we obtain a more complete form of the Gibbs-Duhem equation, at least for
 binary systems, given in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BinaryGibbsDuhem"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=SdT-VdP+n_{1}d\mu_{1}+n_{2}d\mu_{2}\label{eq:BinaryGibbsDuhem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although we will 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalize
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 this equation still further, this equation is powerful! The author refers
 to this equation as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Swiss army knife
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for understanding degrees of freedom and the phase rule, and also for classifyi
ng and interpreting phase diagrams of all kinds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
