status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Degrees of Freedom
\end_layout

\end_inset

The Gibbs-Duhem Equation and Degrees of Freedom
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, as we look at equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BinaryGibbsDuhem"

\end_inset

, how many total variables do we have? The answer is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

four,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 including T (temperature), P (pressure), and two chemical potentials (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{2}$
\end_inset

).
 But if we ask (for the case of a single phase) how many variables we need
 to control to establish thermodynamic equilibrium, the answer is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

three.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 For example, if we fix temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $dT=0$
\end_inset

), pressure (
\begin_inset Formula $dP=0$
\end_inset

), and the chemical potential of component 1 (
\begin_inset Formula $d\mu_{1}=0$
\end_inset

), then according to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BinaryGibbsDuhem"

\end_inset

 the other chemical potential must also be fixed (
\begin_inset Formula $d\mu_{2}=0$
\end_inset

).
 In other words, there are three 
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "$\\underline{F}$"
description "Degrees of freedom"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
degrees of freedom
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
degrees of freedom
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which we refer to by the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Later we will understand degrees of freedom to be the number of thermodynamic
 variables that need to be fixed to establish equilibrium, or alternatively,
 the number of thermodynamic variables that can be independently varied
 without a change in the number of phases present in our system.
 We should also note in passing that we get a hint of the (
\begin_inset Formula $C+2$
\end_inset

) term in the familiar 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gibbs phase rule
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gibbs phase rule
\end_layout

\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GibbsPhaseRule"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underline{F}=(C+2)-\underline{P}\label{eq:GibbsPhaseRule}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the (
\begin_inset Formula $C+2$
\end_inset

) term, C stands for the number of components (
\begin_inset Formula $d\mu_{1},d\mu_{2}$
\end_inset

) and the 2 stands for temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $dT$
\end_inset

) and pressure (
\begin_inset Formula $dP$
\end_inset

), or in other words, (
\begin_inset Formula $C+2$
\end_inset

) is the total number of thermodynamic variables.
 Note that we have employed a different symbol to represent the number of
 phases (
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{P}$
\end_inset

) to differentiate this from pressure (
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

).
 If we add another component (component 3), then we would have to add a
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{3}\mu_{3}$
\end_inset

 term to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BinaryGibbsDuhem"

\end_inset

.
 Now let's see what happens when we have more than one phase, which means
 adding a second Gibbs-Duhem equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Phase Rule
\end_layout

\end_inset

Using the Gibbs-Duhem Equation to Derive the Phase Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let keep it simple by limiting ourselves to a single-component system (C=1).
 The relevant version of the Gibbs-Duhem equation in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BinaryGibbsDuhem"

\end_inset

 would become equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unaryGibbsDuhem"

\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=SdT-VdP+nd\mu\label{eq:unaryGibbsDuhem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where we have dropped the subscripts for component 1, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}d\mu_{1}=nd\mu$
\end_inset

.
 But now let's imagine that we have two phases, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, in equilibrium along the phase boundary in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:A-two-phase-boundary"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/PTalphabeta.svg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A two-phase boundary in a P-T phase diagram
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:A-two-phase-boundary"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the moles are distributed between the two phases, it is not necessarily
 true that 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{\alpha}=n^{\beta}$
\end_inset

, where the superscripts refer to the two phases.
 The same can be said of entropy or volume.
 Imagine ice floating in water.
 The two phases (solid, liquid) are in equilibrium, which we know by the
 fact that the temperature remains constant as long as there is any significant
 amount (moles, volume) of ice.
 But once all the ice melts, the water is free to rise in temperature.
 So what we need to do is to write two Gibbs-Duhem equations, one for the
 alpha phase (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:alphaunaryGD"

\end_inset

) and one for the beta phase (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:betaunaryGD"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=S^{\alpha}dT-V^{\alpha}dP+n^{\alpha}d\mu\label{eq:alphaunaryGD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=S^{\beta}dT-V^{\beta}dP+n^{\beta}d\mu\label{eq:betaunaryGD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's combine these two equations to eliminate one thermodynamic variable,
 e.g., the chemical potential (d
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

), to arrive at equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dMUueliminate"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{S}{n}\right)^{\alpha}dT-\left(\frac{V}{n}\right)^{\alpha}dP=-d\mu=\left(\frac{S}{n}\right)^{\beta}dT-\left(\frac{V}{n}\right)^{\beta}dP\label{eq:dMUueliminate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reorganizing, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dMUueliminate"

\end_inset

 becomes equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PreClausClap"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\left(\frac{V}{n}\right)^{\beta}-\left(\frac{V}{n}\right)^{\alpha}\right]dP=\left[\left(\frac{S}{n}\right)^{\beta}-\left(\frac{S}{n}\right)^{\alpha}\right]dT\label{eq:PreClausClap}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Think for a minute about what equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PreClausClap"

\end_inset

 means.
 For a single-phase in a single-component system, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:unaryGibbsDuhem"

\end_inset

 tells us that two thermodynamic potentials must be fixed in order to establish
 the equilibrium state.
 As pointed out above, in order to fix the chemical potential (
\begin_inset Formula $d\mu=0$
\end_inset

), we have to fix both temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $dT=0$
\end_inset

) and pressure (
\begin_inset Formula $dP=0$
\end_inset

).
 But now that we have two phases in equilibrium (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{\alpha}=\mu^{\beta}$
\end_inset

), we only need fix one variable.
 In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PreClausClap"

\end_inset

 if pressure is fixed (
\begin_inset Formula $dP=0$
\end_inset

), then temperature must also be fixed (
\begin_inset Formula $dT=0$
\end_inset

), or vice versa; so we have decreased the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

degrees of freedom
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by one by adding the second Gibbs-Duhem equation (the second phase in equilibri
um with the first).
 (Note: It is assumed that the molar volumes and molar entropies of the
 two phases are constant.) In other words, the coexistence of two phases
 in thermodynamic equilibrium requires the writing of two Gibbs-Duhem equations-
-one for each phase (equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:alphaunaryGD"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:betaunaryGD"

\end_inset

).
 This clearly demonstrates that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
degrees of freedom
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
degrees of freedom
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

) equals the total number of thermodynamic variables, which equals the number
 of components plus 2 (for temperature and pressure) or (
\begin_inset Formula $C+2$
\end_inset

) minus the number of Gibbs-Duhem equations, which is equal to the number
 of phases in equilibrium (
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{P}$
\end_inset

).
 We have thereby derived the Gibbs Phase Rule in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GibbsPhaseRule"

\end_inset

.
 Note that if we have three phases in thermodynamic equilibrium in a single-comp
onent system (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{\alpha}=\mu^{\beta}=\mu^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

), we would have to add an additional Gibbs-Duhem equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gammaGibbsDuhem"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=S^{\gamma}dT-V^{\gamma}dp+n^{\gamma}d\mu\label{eq:gammaGibbsDuhem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this equation and equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:alphaunaryGD"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:betaunaryGD"

\end_inset

 we could write equations like equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PreClausClap"

\end_inset

 for each of the three phase boundaries meeting at what is known as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

triple point,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as in the P-T diagram for water in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic PT H2O"

\end_inset

.
 We could then eliminate one of the two remaining thermodynamic variables,
 e.g., temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $dT$
\end_inset

), giving us equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DblClapClaus"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\left[\left(\frac{V}{n}\right)^{\beta}-\left(\frac{V}{n}\right)^{^{\alpha}}\right]}{\left[\left(\frac{S}{n}\right)^{\beta}-\left(\frac{S}{n}\right)^{\alpha}\right]}dP=dT=\frac{\left[\left(\frac{V}{n}\right)^{\gamma}-\left(\frac{V}{n}\right)^{\alpha}\right]}{\left[\left(\frac{S}{n}\right)^{\gamma}-\left(\frac{S}{n}\right)^{\alpha}\right]}dP\label{eq:DblClapClaus}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

