\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that all molar volumes and molar entropies are constants and non-zero,
 there is only one possible solution to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DblClapClaus"

\end_inset

, namely that 
\begin_inset Formula $dP$
\end_inset

 must be zero.
 By adding the third Gibbs-Duhem equation for the third phase (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

), we end up with zero degrees of freedom.
 In fact, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

triple point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of water is something you can look up in a handbook, 273.16K (0.01
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}$
\end_inset

C) and 0.00604 atm, and can only be changed by increasing the number of component
s (for example, by doping water with salt, as is done to lower its freezing
 point at constant pressure, which we describe later).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You probably saw equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PreClausClap"

\end_inset

 in prior courses (e.g., chemical or materials thermodynamics), but in a slightly
 different form, as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ClausClapBIG"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{dP}{dT}\right)_{eq}=\frac{\left[\left(\frac{S}{n}\right)^{\beta}-\left(\frac{S}{n}\right)^{\alpha}\right]}{\left[\left(\frac{V}{n}\right)^{\beta}-\left(\frac{V}{n}\right)^{\alpha}\right]}\label{eq:ClausClapBIG}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 stand for molar entropy and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 stand for molar volume, this equation becomes the well-known Clausius-Claypeyro
n equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ClausClapReal"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{dP}{dT}\right)_{eq}=\frac{\Delta S^{\alpha\rightarrow\beta}}{\Delta V^{\alpha\rightarrow\beta}}=\frac{\Delta H^{\alpha\rightarrow\beta}}{T_{eq}\Delta V^{\alpha\rightarrow\beta}}\label{eq:ClausClapReal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
since in equilibrium the free energy difference is zero, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G^{\alpha\rightarrow\beta}=0$
\end_inset

, which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H^{\alpha\rightarrow\beta}=T_{eq}\Delta S^{\alpha\rightarrow\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 As you already know, this is a powerful equation for P-T diagrams.
 Given the molar volume difference between alpha and beta phases, from the
 slope of their P-T equilibrium phase boundary at a chosen 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{eq}$
\end_inset

 we can calculate the enthalpy (and entropy) of the phase transformation,
 or vice versa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before moving on, we must make one clarification regarding the number of
 components.
 It would seem that the number of components should be 2 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{H_{2}O}$
\end_inset

 system, one each for hydrogen and oxygen.
 However, if the ratio of hydrogen-to-oxygen remains constant for all phases
 in the system, namely H:O remains 2:1, then we can consider this as a one-compo
nent system.
\end_layout

