\begin_layout Standard
In section 2.1 we spoke of the Gibbs-Duhem equation as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Swiss army knife
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of phase equilibrium thermodynamics.
 We have used it thus far to determine the degrees of freedom in a single-phase,
 one-component system.
 We have added second and then third phases in equilibrium (and therefore
 second and third Gibbs-Duhem equations) to derive Gibbs' Phase Rule.
 And we have used it to derive the Clausius-Clapeyron equation.
 Now we will use it to derive an overarching classification scheme for 
\shape italic
all
\shape default
 phase diagrams.
 We acknowledge Professor Arthur Pelton of Ã‰cole Polytechnique Montreal
 as the originator of this powerful classification scheme 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pelton_phase_1975"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First of all, let's generalize the Gibbs-Duhem equation to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:GeneralizedGD"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=SdT-VdP+\Sigma n_{i}d\mu_{i}=\Sigma Q_{i}d\phi_{i}\label{eq:GeneralizedGD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

 stands for the various thermodynamic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

potentials
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}$
\end_inset

 stands for the corresponding 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conjugate extensive variables.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 In Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Thermopotsconjextvars"

\end_inset

