\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Type II diagrams are plots of a thermodynamic potential (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

) vs.
 a ratio of conjugate extensive variables (
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{j}/Q_{k}$
\end_inset

).
 (Later we will prove that fixing a ratio of conjugate extensive variables
 is tantamount to fixing their thermodynamic potentials.) Type III diagrams
 are plots of one ratio of thermodynamic potentials vs.
 another, in other words 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i}/Q_{k}$
\end_inset

.
