 phase diagrams for each case are given in the second row of diagrams.
 For example, a conventional P-T diagram like that of water is a good example
 of a Type I diagram.
 However, you may have noticed a couple of anomalies in the other 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

representative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 diagrams.
 For example, the schematic (and easy to recognize) Type II binary eutectic
 diagram does not have 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B}/n_{A}$
\end_inset

 as its x-axis.
 There is a good reason for this.
 Think of what happens if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{A}$
\end_inset

 go to zero.
 This would result in an infinite value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B}/n_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Instead, we use mole fraction (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}=n_{B}/(n_{A}+n_{B})$
\end_inset

), which is zero for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B}=0$
\end_inset

 and unity for 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{A}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Note in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:PeltonScheme"

\end_inset

