\begin_inset Formula $n_{A}/n_{B}$
\end_inset

, which is just the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B}/n_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 The other anomaly is that we seldom, if ever, see Type III ternary diagrams
 in rectilinear form, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{C}/n_{A}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B}/n_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 The reason is pretty obvious.
 Pure 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

end-member
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 A, using phase diagram parlance to be discussed later (
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B}=n_{C}=0$
\end_inset

), is at the origin of this plot, but pure end-members B and C are at infinity
 on the x- and y-axes, respectively.
 We can thank J.
 Willard Gibbs for introducing the now universally employed 
