\begin_layout Subsection
The Ellingham-Richardson Diagram
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1944, it was observed (by Ellingham) that plots of standard free energy
 of oxidation of metals to oxides had essentially the same slope (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G^{o}\approx A+BT;B\approx const$
\end_inset

) as long as the reaction was written per mole of oxygen gas 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{2}(g)$
\end_inset

 as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ellingham eq"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2\frac{x}{y}\mathrm{M(s)}+O_{2}(g)\rightleftharpoons\frac{2}{y}M_{x}O_{y}\label{eq:Ellingham eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where M in this equations represents a metal.
 For example, if we are dealing with the oxide 
\begin_inset Formula $MO$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $x=y=1$
\end_inset

), equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ellingham eq"

\end_inset

 simplifies to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell monoxide"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2\mathrm{M(s)}+O_{2}(g)\rightleftharpoons2MO(s)\label{eq:Ell monoxide}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But we might be dealing with a different metal, N, which forms the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $x=2,\,y=3$
\end_inset

), for which equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ellingham eq"

\end_inset

 becomes equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell N2O3"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{4}{3}N(s)+\mathrm{O_{2}}\left(g\right)\rightleftharpoons\frac{2}{3}N_{2}O_{3}\label{eq:Ell N2O3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if we subtract equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell N2O3"

\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell monoxide"

\end_inset

, the oxygen term cancels out and we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell subtract"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{2M\left(s\right)+\frac{2}{3}N_{2}O_{3}\rightleftharpoons2MO\left(s\right)+\frac{4}{3}N\left(s\right)}\label{eq:Ell subtract}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a powerful capability to determine whether, thermodynamically speaking,
 a given metal will reduce another's oxide or vice versa, as we show later.
 There is a simple rationale for all oxidation reactions having nearly the
 same slope on an 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ellingham diagram
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ellingham diagram
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Let's consider the reaction of calcium to calcium oxide as in equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell Calcia"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2\mathrm{Ca}(s)+\mathrm{O_{2}}\left(g\right)\rightleftharpoons\mathrm{2CaO}(s)\label{eq:Ell Calcia}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overall standard free energy of reaction can be determined by equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell deltaG"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G^{o}=\Delta H^{o}-T\Delta S^{o}\approx A+BT\label{eq:Ell deltaG}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What we are interested in is the Ellingham slope (
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

) in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell deltaG"

\end_inset

, which amounts to the change in standard entropy as given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell Entropy Calcia"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta S^{o}=2S_{CaO(s)}^{o}-2S_{Ca(s)}^{o}-S_{\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}}^{o}\label{eq:Ell Entropy Calcia}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we consult thermodynamic data for the three terms on the right side of
 equation, we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Calcia data"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta S^{o}=2\left(38.1-41.6\right)-205.1=-212.1\mathrm{\frac{J}{mole\cdot K}}\label{eq:Calcia data}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be seen that the first two terms, the standard entropy terms of the
 two solids (calcium oxide, calcium), roughly cancel and that the overall
 value is dominated by the standard entropy of the oxygen gas (the third
 term).
 Hence, the slopes of all oxidation reactions on Ellingham diagrams involving
 solid metals and oxides will be very similar, owing to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $B=-\Delta S^{o}\approx S_{O_{2}(g)}^{o}$
\end_inset

in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell deltaG"

\end_inset

.
 An actual Ellingham diagram is shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-Ellingham-diagram"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

