\begin_layout Standard
At first, this may seem like a complicated diagram.
 However, the following discussion and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

case studies
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 should help to simplify it and demonstrate its usefulness.
 As can be seen there are three different nomographic scales on the sides
 of the diagram.
 These were added by Richardson; hence, the diagram is often referred to
 the Richardson-Ellingham diagram.
 We will highlight each of these scales as we come to them.
 First let's consider three ways to arrive at a specific 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\,\mathrm{or\,}\Delta G^{o},T$
\end_inset

 coordinate on the diagram.
 Consider the reaction of Ti with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}$
\end_inset

 to yield 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{TiO_{2}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $1000^{o}C$
\end_inset

.
 From the line and the diagram legend we know that both the metal and the
 oxide are solids at this temperature, because we do not encounter an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

M
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 symbol (where the metal melts) until much higher temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $T\sim1650^{o}C$
\end_inset

), and there is no boxed 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

M
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 symbol, which stands for the melting point of the oxide.
 This means that the oxide melts at a temperature above the melting point
 of the metal, however no thermodynamic data are provided for higher temperature
s.
 Note: a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 symbol is fairly rare and corresponds to the boiling point of the metal,
 as in the case of Mg and Ca, the bottommost lines on the diagram.
 The large increase in slope at such a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 point is due to the fact that both reactants on the left side of the Ellingham
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ellingham eq"

\end_inset

 are in gaseous form (oxygen gas plus metal vapor) and therefore contribute
 to the entropy or slope of the line.
\end_layout

