\begin_layout Standard
The three ways to reach a specific coordinate are illustrated in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Three-paths-to"

\end_inset

.
 The first way or path (1) to reach the coordinates in question is by what
 I call 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direct read.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The topmost horizontal line of the Ellingham diagram, directly below the
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{H_{2}}/p_{H_{2}O}\,\mathrm{or\,}p_{CO}/p_{CO_{2}}$
\end_inset

 nomographic scales, is the line of zero 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G^{o}$
\end_inset

.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $1000^{o}C$
\end_inset

 we draw an arrow down from this line until we hit the line representing
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ti/TiO_{2}}$
\end_inset

 equilibrium at a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G^{o}\sim-690kJ/mole$
\end_inset

.
 This is illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Three-paths-to"

\end_inset

.
 The second path (2) to reach the same coordinates is to use the Ellingham
 relation in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ell deltaG"

\end_inset

.
 This is also illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Three-paths-to"

\end_inset

.
 It is important to realize where the coordinates (0,0) occur on the diagram.
 On the very left of the Ellingham diagram in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-Ellingham-diagram"

\end_inset

 is a vertical line with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

0 K
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 indicated.
 Since the x-axis is in degrees C, the absolute zero in degrees Kelvin is
 to the left another 
\begin_inset Formula $-273.15^{o}C$
\end_inset

.
 So the actual (0,0) point of the Ellingham diagram is at the top left corner
 where the line which passes through the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

C
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

H
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 points makes an angle with the horizontal line of zero 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G^{o}$
\end_inset

.
 This is a very important point on the Ellingham diagram, which I tend to
 call the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

O
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 point (O for oxygen) and later the O-fulcrum.
 Starting at the O-point, we can draw the 
\begin_inset Formula $A+BT$
\end_inset

 line from the origin as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Three-paths-to"

\end_inset

.
 One can crudely think of this in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H^{o}-T\Delta S^{o}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ti/TiO_{2}}$
\end_inset

 equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the way, there is perfectly good thermodynamic reason why Ellingham did
 not extend the lines on the diagram below 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{o}C$
\end_inset

.
 You may recall from your basic thermodynamics background that the heat
 capacity of a solid begins to vary dramatically below its 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Debye
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 temperature approaching absolute zero.
 This would make for large deviations from linearity of the lines on the
 Ellingham diagram below 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{o}C$
\end_inset

 approaching 
\begin_inset Formula $0K$
\end_inset

; hence, the lines terminate at 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{o}C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third way or path to reach the same coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G^{o}\sim-690kJ/mole$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $1000^{o}C$
\end_inset

 requires some explanation.
 As found in basic chemistry textbooks we know from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:deltaGandQ"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G=\Delta G^{o}+RT\ln Q\label{eq:deltaGandQ}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G$
\end_inset

 of a reaction is related to the standard free energy of that reaction plus
 a second term that depends upon the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

activity quotient
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or Q.
 In the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ti/TiO_{2}}$
\end_inset

 this becomes equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:deltaGTiO2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G=\Delta G^{o}+RT\ln\frac{a_{TiO_{2}}}{a_{Ti}p_{O_{2}}}\label{eq:deltaGTiO2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the activities of the solid phases can be assumed to be unity (assuming
 pure metal and oxide) and the activity of oxygen is given by its partial
 pressure.
 However, if the metal and oxide are in equilibrium we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G=0$
\end_inset

, yielding the following equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:deltavsKeq"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G^{o}=-RT\ln K_{eq}=-RT\ln\frac{1}{p_{O_{2}}^{eq}}=RT\ln p_{O_{2}}^{eq}\label{eq:deltavsKeq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}^{eq}$
\end_inset

 is the oxygen partial pressure where 
\begin_inset Formula $Ti(s)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $TiO_{2}(s)$
\end_inset

 are in equilibrium.
 In effect, path (3) is a line with zero intercept and a slope of 
\begin_inset Formula $R\ln p_{_{O_{2}}}^{eq}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 temperature, as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Three-paths-to"

\end_inset

.
 We can solve mathematically for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}^{eq}$
\end_inset

 by plugging 
\begin_inset Formula $-690kJ/mole$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G^{o}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1000^{o}C$
\end_inset

 or rather 1273K into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:deltavsKeq"

\end_inset

 to arrive at a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $4.9\times10^{-29}atm$
\end_inset

, for which the 
\begin_inset Formula $\log p_{O_{2}}^{eq}$
\end_inset

 (base 10) is -28.3.
 This is where the nomographic scale comes in handy.
 If we draw a line from the origin or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

O-point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 through the coordinates in question (the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ti/TiO_{2}}$
\end_inset

 line at 
\begin_inset Formula $1000^{o}C$
\end_inset

) to the 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

 nomographic scale, we get approximately the same value.
 Keep in mind that this is really a log scale, so we must interpolate the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

logs,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for example one quarter of the way from 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-28}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-30}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-28.5}$
\end_inset

 and definitely not 
\begin_inset Formula $5\times10^{-29}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $5\times10^{-28}$
\end_inset

.
 So we have a short cut or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

easy button
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for finding the 
\begin_inset Formula $\log p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

 value for any set of coordinates on the Ellingham diagram.
 Simply take a ruler and connect it from the O-point through the coordinates
 in question and read the 
\begin_inset Formula $\log p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

 value off the nomographic scale.
 Since all lines radiate from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

O-point,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 I tend to refer to this point as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

O-fulcrum.
 You will note on the Ellingham diagram that all the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tick
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 marks on the O-nomographic scale point back to the O-fulcrum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, achieving such a low oxygen partial pressure is impossible with
 even the best available vacuum systems.
 That is where the outer two nomographic scales come in.
 These involve so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

buffer gas systems.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Consider the reaction of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:COCO2buffer"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2\mathrm{CO(g)}+\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}\rightleftharpoons2\mathrm{CO_{2}(g)}\label{eq:COCO2buffer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's flow an arbitrary mixture of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{CO(g)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{CO_{2}(g)}$
\end_inset

 through a furnace at 1 atm total pressure.
 The equilibrium constant would be given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:COCO2equil"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
