\begin_layout Standard
To summarize, Ellingham diagrams are characterized by the following features:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Curves in Ellingham diagrams for the formation of metallic oxides are basically
 straight lines with a positive slope.
 The slope is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S$
\end_inset

, which is fairly constant with temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The lower position of a metal's line in the Ellingham diagram, the greater
 is the stability of its oxide.
 For example, the line for Al (oxidation of aluminum) is found to be below
 that for Fe (formation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Fe_{2}O_{3}}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Stability of metallic oxides decreases with increasing temperature.
 Highly unstable oxides like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Ag_{2}O}$
\end_inset

 and HgO easily undergo thermal decomposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A reduced substance (such as a metal), whose Gibbs free energy of formation
 is lower on the diagram at a given temperature, will reduce an oxide whose
 free energy of formation is higher on the diagram.
 For example, metallic aluminum can reduce iron oxide to metallic iron,
 with the aluminum itself being oxidized to aluminum oxide.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The greater the gap between any two lines, the greater the effectiveness
 of the reducing agent corresponding to the lower line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Two More Type I Phase Diagrams
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So regardless of the method used to obtain the driving force, it is obvious
 that that driving force is negative; reaction 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Mn/MnOrxn"

\end_inset

 will proceed to the right and Mn metal will be oxidized to its oxide.
 This also allows us to see that we can make a Type I phase diagram out
 of each "line" (or metal/oxide pair) on the Ellingham diagram.
 If we consider the Mn/MnO "line" in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:EllinghamPD"

\end_inset

, it follows that a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direct read
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 arrow from any set of coordinates above the line (corresponding oxygen
 pressures larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}^{eq}$
\end_inset

) to the equilibrium Mn/MnO line will be negative, i.e., the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G$
\end_inset

 will be negative so the oxide will be favored.
 On the other hand, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

direct read
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 arrow from any set of coordinates below the line (corresponding to oxygen
 pressures smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}^{eq}$
\end_inset

) to the equilibrium Mn/MnO line will be positive, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G$
\end_inset

 will be positive so the reaction of does not proceed; the metal will be
 stable.
 Therefore manganese oxide exists everywhere above the "line" and manganese
 metal exists everywhere below the "line." But there are two different forms
 of manganese metal and therefore two Type I phase boundaries: one between
 the solid oxide and the solid metal, below 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}(Mn)$
\end_inset

, and another between the solid oxide and the liquid metal, above 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}(Mn)$
\end_inset

.
 So at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}(Mn)$
\end_inset

 we get a Type I triple point.
 The vertical phase boundary at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}(Mn)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the melting of Mn; solid Mn is stable to the left and liquid
 Mn is stable to the right.
 This vertical line intersects the other two at the triple point, where
 both solid and liquid Mn exist in equilibrium with solid MnO.
\end_layout

