\mu_{A}^{o}(s)\simeq\mu_{A}^{o}(\ell)+RT\ln X_{A}(\ell)\label{eq:NegSS3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging, we obtain equation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-RT\ln X_{A}(\ell)\simeq\mu_{A}^{o}(\ell)-\mu_{A}^{o}(s)\label{eq:NegSS4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But the right side of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS4"

\end_inset

 is simply the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G_{m}$
\end_inset

 of melting of component A per mole, which we know to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{m}-T\Delta S_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 At the melting point (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}$
\end_inset

) we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G_{m}=0$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{m}=T_{m}\Delta S_{m}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S_{m}=\Delta H_{m}/T_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 However, the temperature of equilibrium in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NegSSliquidus"

\end_inset

 is not the melting temperature.
 Modern software packages can account for changes in enthalpy and entropy
 for pure liquid and solid A at different temperatures.
 But we can at least make an estimate of what might happen by employing
 a further simplification, and assume that the enthalpy of melting is approximat
ely constant and does not change significantly with temperature.
 This is often referred to as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Delta c_{p}\approx0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 approximation, namely that the difference in heat capacities between pure
 solid A and pure liquid A is negligible such that the enthalpy of melting
 is approximately temperature-independent.
 This gives the following equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS5"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{m}=\Delta H_{m}-T\Delta S_{m}\simeq\Delta H_{m}-T\left(\frac{\Delta H_{m}}{T_{m}}\right)\simeq\Delta H_{m}\left[1-\frac{T}{T_{m}}\right]\label{eq:NegSS5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By plugging this into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS4"

\end_inset

 we arrive at equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS6"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-RT\ln X_{A}(\ell)\simeq\Delta H_{m}(A)\left[1-\frac{T}{T_{m}(A)}\right]\label{eq:NegSS6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is a rough estimate of the point on the liquidus curve in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NegSSliquidus"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, we can solve the same equation for any temperature, starting with
 the melting temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}(A)$
\end_inset

, for which the right side of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS6"

\end_inset

 is zero.
 This requires that the mole fraction of A in the liquid be unity, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}(\ell)=1$
\end_inset

 or pure A, corresponding to the top of the liquidus in diagram 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NegSSliquidus"

\end_inset

.
 As we decrease the input temperature, the right side of the equation becomes
 increasingly positive, corresponding to smaller and smaller fractional
 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\ell)$
\end_inset

 decreasing from unity to go along with the steady reduction in the liquidus
 temperature, as shown schematically in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NegSSliquidus"

\end_inset

.
 By writing the corresponding equation for the B-liquidus at the other side
 of the phase diagram, again assuming negligible solid solution and ideal
 liquid behavior, we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS7"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-RT\ln X_{B}(\ell)\simeq\Delta H_{m}(B)\left[1-\frac{T}{T_{m}(B)}\right]\label{eq:NegSS7}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both liquidus lines (actually curves) are captured schematically in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NegSSEutectic"

\end_inset

.
 They fall away from the pure end-members, A and B, and can be extended
 far beyond the horizontal line shown on the figure.
 The horizontal line is where the two liquidus curves intersect.
 At this point, the same liquid solution is in equilibrium with both solids
 A and B, and equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS6"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS7"

\end_inset

 are simultaneously satisfied.
 According to the phase rule, there are three phases in equilibrium and
 there are no degrees of freedom.
 We have arrived at an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

invariant point,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which you know well as a binary eutectic.
\end_layout

