\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Binary isomorphous phase diagram.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:BinIsomorph"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's start with the two-phase equilibrium between liquid solution and solid
 solution as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BinIsomorph"

\end_inset

 and as expressed by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IsoM1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{A}(\ell)=\mu_{A}(s)\label{eq:IsoM1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, as per equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS2"

\end_inset

 we can replace each side of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IsoM1"

\end_inset

 with the appropriate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{A}^{o}+RT\ln a_{A}$
\end_inset

 term, giving us equation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{A}^{o}(\ell)+RT\ln a_{A}(\ell)=\mu_{A}^{o}(s)+RT\ln a_{A}(s)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging this equation and substituting mole fractions in place of activities
 (we are assuming both solutions to be ideal), we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IsoM2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
RT\ln\frac{X_{A}(s)}{X_{A}(\ell)}=\mu_{A}^{o}(\ell)-\mu_{A}^{o}(s)\label{eq:IsoM2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The right side of this equation is the free energy of melting per mole of
 pure A, which we previously approximated by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS5"

\end_inset

.
 Making the same simplifying approximation and rearranging, we obtain equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IsoM3"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
RT\ln\frac{X_{A}(s)}{X_{A}(\ell)}\simeq\Delta H_{m}(A)\left[1-\frac{T}{T_{m}(A)}\right]\label{eq:IsoM3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation only gives us the ratio of mole fractions of component A at
 a given equilibrium temperature.
 Fortunately, an analogous equation can be derived for component B:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
RT\ln\frac{X_{B}(s)}{X_{B}(\ell)}\simeq\Delta H_{m}(B)\left[1-\frac{T}{T_{m}(B)}\right]\label{eq:IsoM3-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each given temperature, we can solve for each ratio in equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IsoM3"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IsoM3-1"

\end_inset

.
 If we let the two ratios be 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=X_{A}(s)/X_{A}(\ell)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=X_{B}(s)/X_{B}(\ell)$
\end_inset

, and remind ourselves of the fact that the mole fractions must sum to unity
 for each solution (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}(s)+X_{B}(s)=1;X_{A}(\ell)+X_{B}(\ell)=1)$
\end_inset

, we can show that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta=\frac{X_{B}(s)}{X_{B}(\ell)}=\frac{1-X_{A}(s)}{1-X_{A}(\ell)}=\frac{1-\gamma X_{A}(\ell)}{1-X_{A}(\ell)}\label{eq:IsoM4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
from which the mole fraction of A on the liquidus can be obtained, namely
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}(\ell)=\left(1-\delta\right)/\left(\gamma-\delta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The mole fraction of A on the solidus can then be obtained from the ratio
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 .
 Of course, to plot rather in terms of the mole fraction of B, one need
 only employ the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}+X_{B}=1$
\end_inset

 relations for each solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This example shows how the binary isomorphous diagram can be estimated for
 an A-B system, given only the two melting points and the enthalpies of
 melting.
 The process above need only be repeated systematically between the melting
 points of the two end-members to arrive at a diagram like the schematic
 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BinIsomorph"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before the development of chemical vapor deposition, currently employed
 to purify silicon to transistor-grade levels (impurities at parts per billion!)
, a method called "zone-refining" was used to clean up crystalline ingots
 of silicon.
 The idea can be understood from the binary isomorphous diagram of Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BinIsomorph"

\end_inset

.
 Let component "B" be silicon.
 If we melt silicon with an impurity content at the left end of the equilibrium
 line in the figure, it can be seen that the solid crystallizing from the
 melt is significantly cleaner.
 Suppose we could isolate this cleaner solid.
 If we could repeat the process with this solid, melting it and crystallizing
 it, the composition of the solid would move progressively to the right,
 toward higher purity silicon.
 In fact, this was accomplished by repeated passes of a localized heater
 along the length of a cylindrical silicon crystal held at nearly its melting
 point.
 The "molten zone" was held in place by surface tension and it concentrated
 impurities and took them along for the ride.
 This happened to impurities with a positive "distribution coefficient,"
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $k=X(s)/X(\ell)>1$
\end_inset

 as in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BinIsomorph"

\end_inset

.
 Impurities with a negative distribution coefficient went the opposite direction
 and were left behind.
 Either way, with each pass of the "molten zone" the central portion of
 the crystalline ingot became more and more pure, as the impurities were
 dragged/left behind at the ends, which were cut off and discarded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimating Solvus Lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is rare when a system satisfies the conditions for a continuous solid
 solution.
 Instead, we see phase separation into two solids at low temperatures as
 on the schematic binary eutectic diagram of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BinEutLines"

\end_inset

.
 These can be entirely different crystal structures as in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BinEutLines"

\end_inset

, described as phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Or they can be the same crystal structure, but phase-separation into phases
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}$
\end_inset

 occurs at low temperature.
 The latter behavior can be described by the 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regular solution model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
regular solution model
\end_layout

\end_inset

 you learned about in solution thermodynamics.
 In the following development, let's assume that the entropy of mixing is
 solely 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

configurational,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 namely that it consists of only the ideal entropy of mixing in equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IdMixEntropy"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta S^{M}=\Delta S^{M,id}=-R\left[X_{A}\ln X_{A}+X_{B}\ln X_{B}\right]\label{eq:IdMixEntropy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, for the excess free energy of mixing, let's assume the symmetrical
 enthalpy of mixing for a Regular solution as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSolndeltaH"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G^{xs}=\Delta H^{M}=\Omega X_{A}X_{B}\label{eq:RegSolndeltaH}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is known as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

interaction parameter.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 It describes how A and B interact upon dissolving in one another.
 For example, the type of phase separation we will describe requires significant
ly large positive values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, which raises the free energy of mixing, especially in the middle of the
 solution (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}\approx X_{B}$
\end_inset

).
 The overall free energy of mixing is the sum of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IdMixEntropy"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSolndeltaH"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G^{M}=\Delta H^{M}-T\Delta S^{M,id}=X_{A}X_{B}+RT\left[X_{A}\ln X_{A}+X_{B}\ln X_{B}\right]\label{eq:IdMixEntropy-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's take the first derivative of this equation with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\partial\Delta G^{M}}{\partial X_{B}}\right)=\Omega(X_{A}-X_{B})+RT\left(\ln X_{B}-\ln X_{A}\right)\label{eq:RegSol1stDer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remember that 
\begin_inset Formula $dX_{A}=-dX_{B}$
\end_inset

 when differentiating.
 It turns out that this is the equation describing the phase boundaries
 of the dome-shaped solvus at any temperature in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SolvusPlot"

\end_inset

.
 We can additional useful information by taking the second and third derivatives
 of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IdMixEntropy-1"

\end_inset

.
 The second derivative is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\partial^{2}\Delta G^{M}}{\partial X_{B}^{2}}\right)=-2\Omega+RT\left[\frac{1}{X_{A}}+\frac{1}{X_{B}}\right]\label{eq:RegSol2ndDer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SolvusPlot.svg
	scale 65

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Simple solvus and free energy of mixing curve for the Regular solution model.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SolvusPlot"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation also has special significance, namely the second derivative
 marks the inflection points in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G^{M}$
\end_inset

 vs composition curve of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SolvusPlot"

\end_inset

.
 Outside of each inflection point, marked with a square, the second derivative
 is positive (the curve is concave up) whereas in the middle the the second
 derivative is negative (the curve is concave down).
 You will discuss in later materials science and engineering coursework
 the importance of these "spinodes," especially with respect to a process
 known as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spinodal decomposition.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To arrive at useful forms of both derivative functions, we need to take
 yet another derivative.
 It turns out that at the very top of the solvus in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SolvusPlot"

\end_inset

 all three derivatives are zero.
 The third derivative of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IdMixEntropy-1"

\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\partial^{3}\Delta G^{M}}{\partial X_{B}^{3}}\right)=RT\left[\frac{1}{X_{A}^{2}}-\frac{1}{X_{B}^{2}}\right]\label{eq:RegSol3rdDer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can begin to put all the derivatives to good use.
 For the third derivative to be zero requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}=X_{B}=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 This tells us that the top of the solvus is at the equimolar composition
 as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SolvusPlot"

\end_inset

.
 But the second derivative is also zero at the top of the solvus.
 For equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSol2ndDer"

\end_inset

 to be zero requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $2\Omega/RT=1/X_{A}+1/X_{B}=1/0.5+1/0.5=4$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=2RT$
\end_inset

.
 We refer to this as the "critical" temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{cr}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{cr}=\Omega/2R$
\end_inset

.
 This is an important relationship.
 Given the critical temperature or top of the solvus in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SolvusPlot"

\end_inset

, we can estimate the interaction parameter.
 Or given the interaction parameter, we can estimate the top of the solvus.
 Now let's plug these results into the first derivative equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSol1stDer"

\end_inset

, also setting it equal to zero:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\ln X_{A}+\ln X_{B}=\ln\frac{X_{B}}{X_{A}}=\frac{\Omega}{RT}(X_{B}-X_{A})=\frac{2RT_{cr}}{RT}(X_{B}-X_{A})\label{eq:RegSoln1stDerMod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or more simply:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln\frac{X_{B}}{X_{A}}=\frac{2T_{cr}}{T}\left(X_{B}-X_{A}\right)\label{eq:RegSolnSolvus}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two solutions (phase boundaries) to this equation.
 For example, if we chose a temperature 80% of the critical temperature
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $T/T_{cr}=0.8$
\end_inset

 the two solutions are at 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}=0.145$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}=0.855$
\end_inset

, the latter being the symmetrical solution (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}=0.145$
\end_inset

).
 In the lower diagram of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SolvusPlot"

\end_inset

 the lowest free energy situation between the two phase boundaries is to
 strike out along the dashed line, meaning an assemblage of two separate
 phases rather than a continuous solid solution, which is at higher free
 energies.
 It is actually easier to isolate T in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSolnSolvus"

\end_inset

 and solve for it by plugging in a composition.
 To obtain the following equation, remember that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}=1-X_{B}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}-X_{A}=X_{B}-(1-X_{B})=2X_{B}-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T=\frac{2T_{cr}(2X_{B}-1)}{\ln\left(\frac{X_{B}}{1-X_{B}}\right)}\label{eq:RegSolSolvusTversion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, don't forget the two solutions at each temperature; the second 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}$
\end_inset

 solution is the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}$
\end_inset

 for the first solution.
 To find the "spinodes," we need to set the second derivative equal to zero.
 The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1/X_{A}+1/X_{B}\right)$
\end_inset

 on the right side of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSol2ndDer"

\end_inset

 can be replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X_{B}+X_{A}\right)/X_{A}X_{B}$
\end_inset

, which is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1/X_{A}X_{B}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For the second derivative to be zero requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $2\Omega/RT=(1/X_{A}+1/X_{B})$
\end_inset

 or:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2\frac{\Omega}{RT}=2\frac{2RT_{cr}}{RT}=\frac{4T_{cr}}{T}=\frac{1}{X_{A}X_{B}}\label{eq:RegSolnSpinode}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inverting both sides of this equation yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{T}{4T_{cr}}=X_{A}X_{B}=(1-X_{B})X_{B}=X_{B}-X_{B}^{2}\label{eq:RegSolnSpinRaw}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This turns out to be a simple quadratic function, which can be readily solved
 for composition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{B}=\frac{1\pm\sqrt{1-4(\frac{T}{4T_{cr}})}}{2}=\frac{1\pm\sqrt{1-4\left(\frac{T}{T_{cr}}\right)}}{2}\label{eq:RegSolSpinFin}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, there are two solutions at every temperature.
 For example, at 
\begin_inset Formula $0.8T_{cr}$
\end_inset

 the two solutions are 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}=$
\end_inset

0.276 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}=$
\end_inset

0.724.
 There is much more to spinodes and spinodal decomposition than these very
 simplified equations, as you will discover in higher level materials coursework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Activity vs.
 Composition Plots
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although computer programs are able to do a far better job predicting the
 liquidus, solidus and solvus lines on Type II or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

binary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 phase diagrams, the previous three sections illustrate how far we can get
 with some very simple models and assumptions.
 In that same vein, we now turn to how thermodynamic activity varies with
