\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Binary Isomorphous Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the binary isomorphous phase diagram in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ActCompBinIso"

\end_inset

.
 As above, we will consider both liquid and solid solutions to behave 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ideally,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 meaning that they each follow Raoult's Law (
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}=X_{i}$
\end_inset

).
 At the melting point of B, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}(B)$
\end_inset

, the activity vs.
 composition plot is very simple, as shown to the right.
 The line follows Raoult's Law, hence the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

RL
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 label.
 Since pure liquid B and pure solid B are in equilibrium at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}(B)$
\end_inset

, the plot will be the same regardless of which we chose to be the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standard state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at that temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/ActCompBinIso2.svg
	lyxscale 200
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Activity vs.
 composition plots for an ideal binary isomorphous system.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:ActCompBinIso"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, consider a temperature midway between the two melting temperatures
 (T*), as depicted in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ActCompBinIso"

\end_inset

.
 It makes sense to chose pure solid B as the standard state, since we are
 well below the melting point of B.
 The plot immediately below the phase diagram shows how the activity changes
 with composition.
 We always start with the phase that is in the same state as the standard
 state.
 In this case we begin at the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}^{o}(s)=1$
\end_inset

 point (top right) and begin working backwards down the dashed Raoult's
 Law line until we reach the two-phase equilibrium between liquid solution
 and solid solution.
 In a two-component system at fixed temperature and pressure the degrees
 of freedom are 2- 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{P}$
\end_inset

, or zero in the two-phase region.
 This requires that both chemical potential and thermodynamic activity be
 constant in this region, marked 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

EQ
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for equilibrium.
 The leftmost regime is seemingly straightforward, since we know that thermodyna
mic activity must go to zero at zero composition.
 But this region is also labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

RL,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 yet the line drawn is far from the dashed line for Raoult's Law.
 The reason is that we are now dealing with a liquid solution on a plot
 for which the standard state is pure B solid.
 In fact, if we extrapolate Raoult's Law in the liquid solution all the
 way to the right side of the activity plot, we obtain the activity of pure
 liquid B (if it could be obtained at this temperature) with respect to
 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

WRT
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) pure solid B being the standard state and having unit activity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the bottommost activity plot, we have chosen pure liquid B to be the
 standard state, having unit activity.
 But here we must start our activity plot in the regime where liquid exists,
 which is on the left side of the phase diagram in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ActCompBinIso"

\end_inset

.
 We know that the activity must be zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}=0,$
\end_inset

 so (0,0) is our starting point.
 Since we have assumed a Raoultian liquid, the activity follows Raoult's
 Law (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

RL
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) until the two-phase equilibrium (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

EQ
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) between liquid and solid solutions, where the activity is constant.
 The rightmost region is also labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

RL
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for Raoult's Law, but is again far from the dashed Raoult's Law line.
 Again, the reason is that we are now dealing with a solid solution on a
 plot for which the standard state is pure B liquid (if it could be obtained
 at this temperature).
 By fitting a line from the (0,0) point through the rightmost circled point
 of the two-phase equilibrium and continuing it to the right side of the
 diagram, we obtain the activity of pure solid B with respect to (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

WRT
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) pure liquid B being the standard state at T*.
 It can be shown that the ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}^{o}(\ell)/a_{B}^{o}$
\end_inset

(s) is the same for the two diagrams.
 Furthermore, it is determined by the free energy of melting or fusion of
 component B, as we will now show.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the two-phase equilibrium between liquid solution and solid solution,
 we can write the following relationships between chemical potential and
 activity.
 For the solid we get equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:StdStateBSOl"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{B}(s)=\mu_{B}^{o}(s)+RT\ln\frac{a_{B}(s)}{a_{B}^{o}(s)}\label{eq:StdStateBSOl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and for the liquid we get equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:StdStateBSOl-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{B}(\ell)=\mu_{B}^{o}(\ell)+RT\ln\frac{a_{B}(\ell)}{a_{B}^{o}(\ell)}\label{eq:StdStateBSOl-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Until now, we have always assumed the standard state activity to be unity,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}^{o}=1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}/a_{i}^{o}=a_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 However, now we can make a choice as to which standard state we set equal
 to unity.
 If we consider the two-phase equilibrium in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ActCompBinIso"

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}(s)=\mu_{B}(\ell)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}(s)=a_{B}(\ell)$
\end_inset

, we can subtract equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:StdStateBSOl-1"

\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:StdStateBSOl"

\end_inset

 to obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:StdStateSubtract"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=\mu_{B}^{o}(s)-\mu_{B}^{o}(\ell)+RT\ln\frac{a_{B}^{o}(\ell)}{a_{B}^{o}(s)}\label{eq:StdStateSubtract}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recognizing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}^{o}(\ell)-\mu_{B}^{o}(s)$
\end_inset

 is the free energy of melting per mole of pure B or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G_{m}(B)$
\end_inset

, we can use the same approximation as in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NegSS5"

\end_inset

, namely that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta c_{p}\approx0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H_{m}(B)$
\end_inset

 is not a function of temperature to obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:StdStateApprox"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
RT\ln\frac{a_{B}^{o}(\ell)}{a_{B}^{o}(s)}\simeq\Delta H_{m}(B)\left[1-\frac{T}{T_{m}(B)}\right]\label{eq:StdStateApprox}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This provides the explanation for how the activity vs.
 composition plots behave in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ActCompBinIso"

\end_inset

.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $T=T_{m}(B)$
\end_inset

 the right side of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:StdStateApprox"

\end_inset

 is zero; the two standard state activities are the same (
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}^{o}(s)=a_{B}^{o}(\ell)=1)$
\end_inset

.
 However, at other temperatures, we have the choice of which standard state
 activity we set equal to unity, hence the two diagrams for the temperature
 T*.
 If we divide both sides of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:StdStateApprox"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $RT$
\end_inset

 and exponentiate, we find that at a fixed temperature less than 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{m}(B)$
\end_inset

 (e.g., T*) the activity ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}^{o}(\ell)/a_{B}^{o}(s)$
\end_inset

 is a constant and is greater than unity, given that the right side of equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:StdStateApprox"

\end_inset

 is now positive.
 If we set 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}^{o}(s)=1$
\end_inset

, it follows that the projected activity of pure liquid B (if it could exist
 at T*) would have an activity greater than unity.
 On the other hand, if we set 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}^{o}(\ell)=1$
\end_inset

 it follows that the projected activity of pure solid B will have a value
 less than unity, as on the lower diagram of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ActCompBinIso"

\end_inset

.
 It should be stressed, however, that Raoult's Law is really 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}=X_{B}a_{B}^{o}$
\end_inset

.
 When dealing with the same 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

phase
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (liquid or solid solution) as the standard state, it is understood that
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}^{o}=1$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

RL
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 line will fall on the dashed line in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ActCompBinIso"

\end_inset

.
 However, when dealing with the opposite 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

phase
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (liquid or solid solution) from the standard state, Raoult's Law will still
 be a line, but its slope will be governed by the activity ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}^{o}(\ell)/a_{B}^{o}(s)$
\end_inset

.
 In the lower two activity plots of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ActCompBinIso"

\end_inset

, we draw a line from the origin to or through the point at which we know
 the activity relative to the opposing standard state scale.
 In the bottom diagram, this linear projection ends at the activity of pure
 B solid with respect to pure B liquid having unit activity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Binary Eutectic Systems with Dilute Solid Solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also draw schematic activity vs.
 composition diagrams for many binary eutectic systems by making the simplifying
 assumption that the solid solutions are "dilute" solutions.
 A dilute solution is one for which the solute (the minor component) behaves
 in a Henry's Law fashion and the solvent (the majority or "host" component)
 behaves in a Raoult's Law fashion.
 In fact, it can be proven that if the solute is Henrian, the solvent must
 be Raoultian.
 In a dilute solution, the solute (B) atoms are only surrounded by A atoms.
 It makes sense that the 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
activity coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Activity coefficient
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{B}$
\end_inset

) in the general equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:activityGen"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{B}=\gamma_{B}X_{B}\label{eq:activityGen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
will not vary with composition over the "dilute" regime until it begins
 to encounter other B atoms in its surroundings, giving us 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Henry's Law
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Henry's Law
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:HenrysLaw"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{B}=\gamma_{B}X_{B};\;\gamma_{B}\neq f(X_{B})\label{eq:HenrysLaw}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's find out what this requires of the solvent, component A.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{B}^{'}$
\end_inset

 is a constant, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $d\ln a_{B}=d\ln X_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 But consider a version of the Gibbs-Duhem equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiluteGibbDuh"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{A}d\mu_{A}+X_{B}d\mu_{B}=X_{A}RTd\ln a_{A}+X_{B}RTd\ln a_{B}=0\label{eq:DiluteGibbDuh}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dividing out the "RT" term and rearranging gives us equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiluteGibbDuh2"

\end_inset

, where we employ our knowledge of the solute behavior (
\begin_inset Formula $d\ln a_{B}=d\ln X_{B}$
\end_inset

) to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $d\ln a_{B}$
\end_inset

 on the right by 
\begin_inset Formula $d\ln X_{B}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d\ln a_{A}=-\frac{X_{B}}{X_{A}}d\ln a_{B}=-\frac{X_{B}}{X_{A}}d\ln X_{B}\label{eq:DiluteGibbDuh2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But, of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\ln X_{B}=dX_{B}/X_{B}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $dX_{B}=-dX_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dX_{A}/X_{A}=d\ln X_{A}$
\end_inset

 such that equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiluteGibbDuh2"

\end_inset

 becomes equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
