\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Method of Tangential Intercepts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/TangIntercept.svg
	scale 65

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Schematic diagram of free energy vs.
 composition of a continuous solution.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Tangent"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Tangent"

\end_inset

 is a schematic diagram of absolute free energy vs.
 composition of a continuous solution in the A-B system.
 This could be a liquid solution or a solid solution.
 The total free energy is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G'=n_{A}\mu_{A}+n_{B}\mu_{B}\label{eq:TangInt1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we divide both sides by (
\begin_inset Formula $n_{A}+n_{B}$
\end_inset

) we arrive at the free energy per mole of solution or equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G=X_{A}\mu_{A}+X_{B}\mu_{B}\label{eq:TangInt2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the total differential, we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt3"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dG=X_{A}d\mu_{A}+\mu_{A}dX_{A}+X_{B}d\mu_{B}+\mu_{B}dX_{B}\label{eq:TangInt3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, from the Gibbs-Duhem equation (per mole of solution) at constant
 temperature and pressure in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiluteGibbDuh"

\end_inset

 we have equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt4"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=X_{A}d\mu_{A}+X_{B}d\mu_{B}\label{eq:TangInt4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's subtract equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt4"

\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt3"

\end_inset

 to obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt5"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dG=\mu_{A}dX_{A}+\mu_{B}dX_{B}=(\mu_{A}-\mu_{B})dX_{A}\label{eq:TangInt5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
since 
\begin_inset Formula $dX_{B}=-dX_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 If we multiply both sides of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt5"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}/dX_{A}$
\end_inset

 we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt6"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{B}\frac{dG}{dX_{A}}=X_{B}\mu_{A}-X_{B}\mu_{B}\label{eq:TangInt6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's add equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt2"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt6"

\end_inset

 to obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt7"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G+X_{B}\frac{dG}{dX_{A}}=\mu_{A}(X_{A}+X_{B})=\mu_{A}\label{eq:TangInt7}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By analogy, we can derive a similar equation for the chemical potential
 of B as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt8"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G+X_{A}\frac{dG}{dX_{B}}=\mu_{B}(X_{A}+X_{B})=\mu_{B}\label{eq:TangInt8}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are very important equations.
 For example, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt8"

\end_inset

 tells us that if we take the slope of the G vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}$
\end_inset

 curve at any point (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}^{'}$
\end_inset

in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Tangent"

\end_inset

) and place the corresponding line on the diagram, the right intercept will
 be the chemical potential of B at that particular composition (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}^{'}$
\end_inset

).
 This follows from the left side of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TangInt8"

\end_inset

.
 The sum of the absolute value of G at that composition plus the product
 of the mole fraction of A (marked as "run" on the diagram) and the slope
 
\begin_inset Formula $dG/dX_{B}$
\end_inset

 (marked "rise/run" on the diagram) yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}$
\end_inset

 at that composition.
 Similarly, at the left end of this tangent line will be the chemical potential
 of component A at that same composition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This procedure is often referred to as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

method of tangential intercepts.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 It is important for several reasons: 1) It conclusively proves that we
 can fix two chemical potentials by fixing the ratio of two conjugate extensive
 variables, in this case the ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B}/n_{A}$
\end_inset

 or rather the mole fraction, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{B}/(n_{A}+n_{B}).$
\end_inset

 2) Given a specific G vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}$
\end_inset

 curve, we can determine the chemical potentials at any composition.
 3) Since we know the chemical potential of the pure end-members A (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{A}^{o}$
\end_inset

) and B (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{B}^{o}$
\end_inset

), namely the extreme ends of each G vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}$
\end_inset

 curve, we can also know the activity at any composition using the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}=\mu_{i}^{o}+RT\ln a_{i}$
\end_inset

 relationship.
 4) Finally, if we have two phases in equilibrium, they must share the same
 common tangent and intercepts so that the chemical potentials and activities
 are the same in both phases.
 We will illustrate this when we draw schematic free energy vs.
 composition curves for actual phase diagrams (below).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Terminal Slopes on Free Energy vs.
 Composition Plots
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be shown that the terminal slopes on a free energy vs.
 composition plot should be infinitely negative as 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and infinitely positive as 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

.
 Let's begin with the regular solution model of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IdMixEntropy-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G^{M}=\Delta H^{M}-T\Delta S^{M,id}=\Omega X_{A}X_{B}+RT\left[X_{A}\ln X_{A}+X_{B}\ln X_{B}\right]\label{eq:RegSolAgain}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first derivative of this equation with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}$
\end_inset

 gives us equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSolDeriv"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial G^{M}}{\partial X_{B}}=\Omega(X_{A}-X_{B})+RT\left[-\ln X_{A}+\ln X_{B}\right]\label{eq:RegSolDeriv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the limit that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

 ) the derivative becomes negative infinity and in the opposite limit where
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 ) the derivative becomes positive infinity.
 These hold true regardless of the size of the interaction parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 What this means is that in any free energy vs.
 composition plots we sketch, the terminal slopes must be 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 at the left and 
\begin_inset Formula $+\infty$
\end_inset

 at the right.
\end_layout

