\begin_layout Standard
At first glance, this would seem to be a T vs.
 mole fraction phase diagram for a binary isomorphous system as in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BinIsomorph"

\end_inset

, which it closely resembles.
 However, this is not the case.
 In a T-X binary isomorphous phase diagram the two phases in equilibrium
 at the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lens
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are liquid solution (prevails at higher temperature) and solid solution
 (prevails at lower temperature).
 In Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:OxideAlloyTypeII"

\end_inset

 the two phases in equilibrium are an oxide AO-BO solid solution (prevails
 at higher 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

) and an alloy A-B solid solution (prevails at lower 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

).
 The x-axis is the mole fraction of B in either phase, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}/(X_{A}+X_{B})$
\end_inset

, which translates into 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{BO}/(X_{AO}+X_{BO})$
\end_inset

 in the oxide solid solution (see the dual x-axis in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:OxideAlloyTypeII"

\end_inset

).
 Both solutions are 1) solid and 2) continuous.
 So this is an oxidation phase diagram.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}^{eq}$
\end_inset

 values at either end of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lens
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 correspond the point of oxidation of pure metal to pure oxide, either A
 to AO (on the left) or B to BO (on the right).
 Since the interpretation of all phase diagrams within a given Type is the
 same, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lens
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 corresponds to two-phase equilibrium between an oxide solid solution (ceramists
 never refer to solid solutions as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

alloys!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) and an alloy solid solution, as at the ends of the tie-line at the selected
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

 in the phase diagram.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact, we can actually simulate the phase diagram in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:OxideAlloyTypeII"

\end_inset

.
 Of course, this is an extremely unique situation, involving continuous
 solid solutions of both phases.
 This would mean that Hume-Rothery rules would need to be satisfied for
 both solid solutions.
 For our simulation, we will assume that both solid solutions behave ideally,
 i.e., they behave according to Raoult's law such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{A}=X_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{B}=X_{B}$
\end_inset

 in the alloy and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{AO}=X_{AO}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{BO}=X_{BO}$
\end_inset

 in the oxide solid solution.
 We begin by writing the oxidation reaction for component A as equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Aoxidrxn"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2A(s)+\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}\rightleftharpoons2AO(s)\label{eq:Aoxidrxn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can write the equilibrium relationship for this reaction as follows in
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AoxideEQK1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{1}=\exp(-\Delta G_{1}^{o}/RT)=\frac{a_{AO}^{2}}{a_{A}^{2}p_{O_{2}}}\label{eq:AoxideEQK1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can evaluate the equilibrium constant 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

 in one of two ways.
 First, we can find the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G_{1}^{o}$
\end_inset

 at 1000K from the Ellingham diagram in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-Ellingham-diagram"

\end_inset

.
 Second, we can use the 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

 nomographic scale on the Ellingham diagram to solve the following equilibrium
 equation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{1}=\frac{a_{AO}^{2}}{a_{A}^{2}p_{O_{2}}}=\frac{1^{2}}{1^{2}p_{O_{2}}^{eq(A/AO)}}\label{eq:PureAAOequil}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are dealing here exclusively with the point at the leftmost end of the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lens
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:OxideAlloyTypeII"

\end_inset

, where essentially pure A metal is in equilibrium with pure AO oxide.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}^{eq(A/AO)}$
\end_inset

 can be established by drawing a line from the O-fulcrum through the 1000K
 intersection of the A/AO line to the O-nomographic scale on the Ellingham
 diagram of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-Ellingham-diagram"

\end_inset

.
 A similar process can be carried out at the right side of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lens
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:OxideAlloyTypeII"

\end_inset

 involving the oxidation reaction for component B as per equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Aoxidrxn-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2B(s)+\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}\rightleftharpoons2BO(s)\label{eq:Aoxidrxn-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
yielding an analogous equilibrium relationship as described by equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PureAAOequil-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{2}=\exp(-\Delta G_{2}^{o}/RT)=\frac{a_{BO}^{2}}{a_{B}^{2}p_{O_{2}}}=\frac{1^{2}}{1^{2}p_{O_{2}}^{eq(B/BO)}}\label{eq:PureAAOequil-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As for the A/AO equilibrium, we can establish the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{2}$
\end_inset

 from either the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G_{2}^{o}$
\end_inset

 value at 1000K from the Ellingham diagram, or alternatively the value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}^{eq(B/BO)}$
\end_inset

 by drawing a line from the O-fulcrum through the 1000K intersection of
 the B/BO line to the O-nomographic scale on the Ellingham diagram of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-Ellingham-diagram"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This gives us the two endpoints of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lens,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but how can we establish the phase boundaries of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lens
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for, say, a given 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

 value as illustrated by the tie line in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:OxideAlloyTypeII"

\end_inset

? This can be accomplished be recognizing that both equilibrium relationships
 of equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PureAAOequil"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PureAAOequil-1"

\end_inset

 must also hold for every 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

 value between the extrema (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}^{eq(A/AO)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}^{eq(B/BO)}$
\end_inset

).
 Furthermore, the situation is simplified by our assumption of Raoultian
 behavior for each solid solution.
 We can therefore write two equilibrium expressions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PureAAOequil-2"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PureAAOequil-3"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{1}=\frac{a_{AO}^{2}}{a_{A}^{2}p_{O_{2}}}=\frac{X_{AO}^{2}}{X_{A}^{2}p_{O_{2}}}\label{eq:PureAAOequil-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{2}=\frac{a_{BO}^{2}}{a_{B}^{2}p_{O_{2}}}=\frac{X_{BO}^{2}}{X_{B}^{2}p_{O_{2}}}\label{eq:PureAAOequil-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking into account that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}+X_{B}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{AO}+X_{BO}=1,$
\end_inset

we can divide equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PureAAOequil-3"

\end_inset

 by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PureAAOequil-2"

\end_inset

 to eliminate the unknown 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

 to arrive at equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BOxOVERAox"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{K_{2}}{K_{1}}=\frac{X_{BO}^{2}X_{A}^{2}}{X_{B}^{2}X_{AO}^{2}}=\frac{(1-X_{AO})^{2}X_{A}^{2}}{(1-X_{A})^{2}X_{AO}^{2}}\label{eq:BOxOVERAox}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the square root of both sides and rearranging, we obtain equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OxAlloyFinal"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{(1-X_{AO})}{X_{AO}}=\left(\frac{K_{2}}{K_{1}}\right)^{1/2}\frac{(1-X_{A})}{X_{A}}\label{eq:OxAlloyFinal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since at each temperature, including 1000K, the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{2}/K_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a constant, we can solve equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OxAlloyFinal"

\end_inset

 for a unique value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{AO}$
\end_inset

 for each inputted value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 We can then plug the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{AO}$
\end_inset

 into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PureAAOequil-2"

\end_inset

 to solve for the corresponding value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 By varying the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}$
\end_inset

, we can solve for individual tie-lines (
\begin_inset Formula $\log p_{O_{2},}X_{A},X_{AO}$
\end_inset

).
 Once again, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}=1-X_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{BO}=1-X_{AO}$
\end_inset

.
 Intrepreting the phase diagram in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:OxideAlloyTypeII"

\end_inset

 is straightforward.
 In each of the single-phase regions there are two degrees of freedom, i.e.,
 to establish thermodynamic equilibrium (in addition to fixing overall pressure
 (1 atm) and temperature (1000K), one would have to fix the overall composition
 (B/A ratio) and the oxygen partial pressure.
 Inside the "lens" however, there is a single degree of freedom.
 If we fix the oxygen partial pressure, both phases' compositions are fixed.
 Alternatively, we need only fix one composition of the two phases in equilibriu
m, say 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}$
\end_inset

, and the composition of the other phase, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{BO}$
\end_inset

, plus the oxygen partial pressure are thereby also fixed.
\end_layout

