\begin_layout Standard
Type I diagrams are distinctive in their absence of tie-lines.
 Areas are always single-phase regions, and lines are always phase boundaries
 between two adjacent phases.
 Type II diagrams are distinctive because of their having tie-lines perpendicula
r to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thermodynamic potential
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

) axis.
 The dashed lines are usually not drawn as in the Type II diagram of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TypeCompare"

\end_inset

; but they are understood.
 In fact, since we can always draw another tie-line between any adjacent
 pair of tie-lines, there is an infinite array of tie-lines within the three
 two-phase regions on the diagram.
 However, when these tie-lines converge to unique three-phase (F=O) invariancies
, these are represented as solid lines perpendicular to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

-axis.
 For example, we are quite familiar with the horizontal invariant lines
 in T vs.
 mole fraction eutectic (as in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BinEutLines"

\end_inset

) or eutectoid diagrams (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Fe-C PD schematic"

\end_inset

).
 So there are two different 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

areas
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Type II diagrams: single-phase regions (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

) and two-phase regions consisting of an infinite array of parallel tie-lines
 perpendicular to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

-axis (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+\beta,\alpha+\gamma,\gamma+\beta$
\end_inset

).
 Type III diagrams are distinctive owing to the presence of tie-triangles
 involving three phases in equilibrium (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta,\mathrm{\,and\,}\gamma$
\end_inset

 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TypeCompare"

\end_inset

).
 They are also distinctive in that tie-lines need neither be parallel nor
 perpendicular to any axis, as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TypeCompare"

\end_inset

.
 In contrast with Type II diagrams, tie-lines for two-phase equilibria are
 typically drawn.
 However, once again since we can always find another tie-line between any
 adjacent pair of tie-lines, so there is an infinite array of tie-lines
 within the two-phase regions on the diagram.
 Furthermore, as these converge to the sides of unique three-phase equilibrium
 triangles, these solid lines become very important, representing the terminal
 compositions of the two phases in equilibrium with that of the third.
 So lines are either phase boundaries of single-phase regions (can be curved)
 or the straight line sides of tie-triangles.
 As can be seen, open 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

areas
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can either be single-phase regions (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

) or tie-triangles.
 These tie-triangles are usually referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compatibility
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 triangles, meaning that the terminal compositions of the three phases are
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compatible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and do not react with one another.
