\begin_layout Standard
The ternary lever rule is applicable to all tie-triangles, and not just
 equilateral ones.
 The best approach is to employ a ruler to measure the length of line segments
 in the specific triangle.
 For example, take the composition marked by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

X
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TernaryLeverRule"

\end_inset

.
 The fraction of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 phase, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is the length of the line segment marked AX divided by the entire length
 of the line drawn from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta-\gamma$
\end_inset

 side of the tie triangle through the overall composition 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

X
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 vertex.
 Similarly, the fractions of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 phases can be determined from their relative line lengths, so we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
f^{\alpha}=\frac{AX}{A\alpha}\\
f^{\beta}=\frac{BX}{B\beta}\\
f^{\gamma}=\frac{CX}{C\gamma}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The three fractions sum to unity.
 It can be readily seen that when this scheme is applied to an equilateral
 triangle, we obtain the axis scheme associated with Gibbs' phase triangle.
