\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hummel's Rules
\end_layout

\end_inset

Hummel's Rules for Ternary Systems with Negligible Solid Solubility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can relax the Raoultian liquid specification in our considerations, but
 if a given ternary phase diagram involves negligible solid solubility it
 can be shown that very specific rules hold for the interpretation of liquidus
 projection diagrams.
 Once we have laid the foundation for interpretation of such Type III phase
 diagrams, we can turn to more sophisticated simulation engines/algorithms
 to help us interpret ternary diagrams with appreciable solid solubility.
 For examples, many metal alloy ternaries fall into the latter category.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to introduce Hummel's Rules (adapted from F.
 A.
 Hummel's class notes and his textbook, 
\emph on
Phase Equilibria in Ceramic Systems
\emph default
, Marcel Dekker, 1984), we need to develop a binary analogy.
 We need to think carefully about how to generate both eutectic and peritectic
 behavior in the absence of solid solubility.
 Conventional binary eutectic and peritectic phase diagrams are displayed
 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BinEutPeri"

\end_inset

.
 We have already described the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

easy melting
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 character of eutectic systems, but the melting/heating reactions are quite
 different between eutectic and peritectic diagrams.
 We can describe them as follows in equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:EutRxn"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:PeriRxn"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha+\beta\rightleftharpoons\mathrm{liquid\,solution}\label{eq:EutRxn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha\rightleftharpoons\beta+\mathrm{liquid\,solution}\label{eq:PeriRxn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In these reactions, the forward arrow stands for heating and the reverse
 arrow stands for cooling.
 From the Greek, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

peritectic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

covered melting.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This can be seen in that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

primary phase field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 (the two-phase area where only 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is in equilibrium with liquid) overhangs or covers the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 phase.
 Another way to describe peritectic melting is that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 phase melts to a liquid of a different composition and another solid (
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

).
 This is referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

incongruent melting,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as described below.
\end_layout

