\begin_layout Standard
But now let's imagine what happens on both diagrams as the solid solubilities,
 namely the solubility of B in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and the solubility of A in 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, go to zero.
 This works for the eutectic system (as in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:NegSSEutectic"

\end_inset

), where the quotation marks around 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

A
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 remind us that thermodynamically speaking, there is no such thing as an
 absolutely 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

