\end_inset

 namely it melts to a liquid of identical composition, AB.
 In fact, we can recognize that this diagram can be thought of as consisting
 of two side-by-side eutectic diagrams: A-AB and AB-B.
 However, this cannot be said of the diagram on the right.
 It similarly has an intermediate compound (AB), however in this case the
 compound (AB) melts 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

incongruently
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to a liquid of a quite different composition (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

peritectic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 composition at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

) and a different solid (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
