\begin_layout Section
Fick's Laws of Diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as there are fundamental laws governing the thermodynamics of materials,
 so there are basic laws governing diffusion or how atoms/ions move around
 in materials.
 Consider the two adjacent planes in an isotropic solid as shown in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffusePlanes"

\end_inset

a:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/DiffPlanes.svg
	width 35text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Schematic of flux between adjacent planes in an isotropic solid.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:DiffusePlanes"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By isotropic, we mean that the diffusion rate of an impurity atom is independent
 of direction.
 The planes are separated by the distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,$
\end_inset

 which we will refer to as the jump distance.
 Each plane has a different areal density of impurity atoms (# per 
\begin_inset Formula $cm^{2}$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{1}$
\end_inset

 on plane 1 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{2}$
\end_inset

 on plane 2.
 Things are simplified by assuming an isotropic solid, since we can consider
 jumps from plane 1 to plane 2 (along the +
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis) to be only one of six possible jump directions (
\begin_inset Formula $\pm x,\pm y,\pm z$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore, the number of atoms jumping from plane 1 to plane 2 during a
 time period 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

 will be equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1to2jumps"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\#_{1\rightarrow2}=\frac{1}{6}\varGamma n_{1}\delta t\label{eq:1to2jumps}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma$
\end_inset

 is the jump frequency of an atom (#/s).
 Similarly, the counter jumps from plane 2 to plane 1 during the same time
 period is equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2to1jumps"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\#_{2\rightarrow1}=\frac{1}{6}\varGamma n_{2}\delta t\label{eq:2to1jumps}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The net flow to the right through an imaginary plane midway between the
 two planes, as in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffusePlanes"

\end_inset

b, is given by subtracting equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2to1jumps"

\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:1to2jumps"

\end_inset

 or equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:net1to2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
net\#_{1\rightarrow2}=\frac{1}{6}\varGamma(n_{1}-n_{2})\delta t\label{eq:net1to2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we define the net flux 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 as the number of atoms passing through a unit 
\begin_inset Formula $cm^{2}$
\end_inset

 area per unit time (
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

), we arrive at equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:net1to2-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
net\#_{1\rightarrow2}=\frac{1}{6}\varGamma(n_{1}-n_{2})\delta t=J\delta t\label{eq:net1to2-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffusePlanes"

\end_inset

b) the flux can be written as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxEq1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J=\frac{1}{6}\varGamma(n_{1}-n_{2})\label{eq:FluxEq1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two immediate observations can be made from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxEq1"

\end_inset

.
 The units of flux are 
\begin_inset Formula $(\#/cm^{2})/s$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, if the area concentration of the impurity is the same on the
 two planes, the net flux will be zero.
 However, this does not indicate a static situation; it only means that
 the flux to the right (
\begin_inset Formula $J_{1}=\frac{1}{6}\varGamma n_{1}$
\end_inset

) is the same as the flux to the left (
\begin_inset Formula $J_{2}=\frac{1}{6}\varGamma n_{2}$
\end_inset

).
 In fact, each of these fluxes can be enormous.
 Net zero flux only requires that their magnitudes be the same, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $J=J_{1}-J_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

