\begin_layout Standard
Substituting for (
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}-c_{2}$
\end_inset

) in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VolDiffPlanes"

\end_inset

, we find that equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxFicks"

\end_inset

 holds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J=\frac{1}{6}\varGamma\alpha(c_{1}-c_{2})=-\frac{1}{6}\varGamma\alpha^{2}\frac{\partial c}{\partial x}\label{eq:FluxFicks}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This important equation tells us that the flux is proportional to the negative
 of the concentration gradient at time t, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{c}=(\partial c/\partial x)_{t}$
\end_inset

, and the proportionality coefficient is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Deq"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=\frac{1}{6}\varGamma\alpha^{2}\label{eq:Deq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where D is the isotropic diffusion coefficient.
 Since the jump frequency (
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma$
\end_inset

) has units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\#/s$
\end_inset

 and the jump distance (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

) has units of 
\begin_inset Formula $cm$
\end_inset

, it follows that the diffusion coefficient will have units of 
\begin_inset Formula $cm^{2}/s$
\end_inset

.
 Many times we will see diffusion coefficients in other units, such as 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{2}/s$
\end_inset

.
 Regardless, we can rewrite equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxFicks"

\end_inset

 as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FicksFirst"

\end_inset

, which is the most common form of Fick's First Law of diffusion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J=-D\frac{\partial c}{\partial x}\label{eq:FicksFirst}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be stressed that the diffusion coefficient of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Deq"

\end_inset

 holds strictly true only for isotropic solids.
 These include amorphous solids (glasses) and cubic crystal structures,
 such as face-centered cubic (fcc), body-centered cubic (bcc), sodium chloride
 (NaCl), fluorite (
\begin_inset Formula $CaF_{2}$
\end_inset

), etc.
 More complex equations describe diffusion in non-cubic systems, e.g., hexagonal
 close-packed (hcp), which are beyond the scope of the present treatment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Random Walk Diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Above we mentioned that lots of jumps are taking place in both directions
 between planes 1 and 2 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffusePlanes"

\end_inset

, even under a condition of zero net-flux.
 Consider the diffusion coefficient of interstitial carbon in fcc 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma-Fe$
\end_inset

, which has been found experimentally to be 
\begin_inset Formula $2.5x10^{-11}m^{2}/s$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $1000^{o}C$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FCCIntJump"

\end_inset

 shows the nearest-neighbor jump distance of an interstitial on a (100)
 plane in the fcc structure.
\end_layout

