\begin_layout Subsection
Steady State Diffusion
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Steady state diffusion
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

steady state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 situation is one in which the local concentration of impurities does not
 change with time, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\partial c/\partial t)_{x}=0$
\end_inset

 at each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 A good example involves the gradual diffusion of hydrogen through the steel
 wall of a pressurized gas tank, as represented schematically in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SteadyState"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SteadyState.svg
	scale 75

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Steady state diffusion of hydrogen through a steel tank wall.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SteadyState"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has been found that hydrogen dissolves to some extent in steel, maintaining
 a constant surface composition on the inner surface of the tank that depends
 upon the tank pressure.
 Since air surrounds the tank and the hydrogen content in air at ground
 level is less than 1 part per million, we can assume the hydrogen content
 on the outside of the tank to be zero.
 Let the equilibrium hydrogen content on the inner surface be 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{H}$
\end_inset

 and the wall thickness be 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

.
 A steady state situation means that the hydrogen content decreases linearly
 with distance from 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{H}$
\end_inset

 at the inner wall to zero at the outer wall (
\begin_inset Formula $x=\xi$
\end_inset

).
 This can be expressed mathematically as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SteadyState"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\partial c}{\partial x}\right)=\frac{c(x=\xi)-c(x=0)}{\xi-0}=\frac{0-c_{H}}{\xi}\label{eq:SteadyState}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plugging this into Fick's First Law of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FicksFirst"

\end_inset

, we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SteadyState2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J=\frac{Dc_{H}}{\xi}\label{eq:SteadyState2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The product 
\begin_inset Formula $D\cdot c_{H}$
\end_inset

 is often called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gas permeability,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 since to be permeable through the solid wall the gas has to be both soluble
 (
\begin_inset Formula $c_{H}$
\end_inset

) and mobile (
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

).
 Gas permeability is given in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $g/cm\cdot s$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $kg/m\cdot s$
\end_inset

, which reflects the product of the diffusion coefficient (
\begin_inset Formula $cm^{2}/s$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{2}/s$
\end_inset

) and the appropriate mass concentration (
\begin_inset Formula $g/cm^{3}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $kg/m^{3}$
\end_inset

).
 Fortunately, the gas permeability of hydrogen through steel is relatively
 small at room temperature.
 Nevertheless, given sufficient time and sufficient diffusion the internal
 gas pressure (and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{H}$
\end_inset

) will gradually decline to yet another steady state situation.
 A compelling demonstration of this effect is the loss of helium from mylar
 balloons.
 Helium rapidly diffuses through typical rubber balloons.
 However, mylar balloons have a thin aluminum metal coating that helps to
 slow down helium diffusion.
 Nevertheless, helium eventually escapes causing the balloon to slowly lose
 buoyancy.
 The situation at any point can be well described by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SteadyState2"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fick's Second Law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The steady state example just described is an exception rather than the
 rule.
 In virtually all other instances of diffusion, the impurity concentration
 at a given point is changing with time.
 For such situations we will need another diffusion law, referred to as
 Fick's Second Law of diffusion.
 Consider the two concentration profiles in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TwoProfiles"

\end_inset

 and what is happening at imaginary planes 1 and 2, in each case separated
 by the distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/TwoCprofiles.svg
	lyxscale 35
	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Two contrasting concentration profiles and the relative fluxes at two planes
 separated by a distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta x$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:TwoProfiles"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fick's First Law in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FicksFirst"

\end_inset

 tells us that the flux is proportional to the negative of the concentration
 gradient at each point.
 Based upon the gradient (slope) at each plane, it can be seen that the
 flux across plane 1 is greater than the flux across plane 2 in the concave-up
 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 profile on the left, and the opposite is true in the concave-down 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 profile on the right.
 We might therefore expect the local concentration between the planes to
 increase with time in the first situation, but decrease with time in the
 second.
 To simplify our discussion, let's assume that the flux is a linear function
 of distance, as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:LinearFlux"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/JLinear.svg
	lyxscale 30
	scale 65

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hypothetical linear flux vs.
 distance relationship that might correspond to the concave-up concentration
 profile in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TwoProfiles"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:LinearFlux"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This might correspond to the first situation in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TwoProfiles"

\end_inset

.
 As can be seen, the flux into the volume between the planes is greater
 than the flux out, so we would expect the impurity concentration in that
 volume to increase with time.
 If we specify an identical area, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, on each plane, we can calculate the number of impurity atoms that are
 added to the volume between the two planes during an increment of time,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

, with the following equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxConcChg"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(J_{1}-J_{2})A\delta t=A\varDelta x\delta c\label{eq:FluxConcChg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the units of flux are 
\begin_inset Formula $(\#/cm^{2})/s$
\end_inset

, when we multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $(J_{1}-J_{2})$
\end_inset

 by the product of area (
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $cm^{2}$
\end_inset

) and time increment (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

), we arrive at the number of impurity atoms that are added to the volume
 between the planes.
 Since the volume in question is just the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta x$
\end_inset

, this amounts to an increment in the impurity concentration (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta c$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\#/cm^{3}$
\end_inset

).
 We can use equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxConcChg"

\end_inset

 to help us derive Fick's Second Law.
 Let's begin by doing a Taylor series expansion of flux around 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{1}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxTaylor"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{2}=J_{1}+\left(\frac{\partial J}{\partial x}\right)\varDelta x\label{eq:FluxTaylor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
again ignoring higher order terms.
 Rearranging equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxTaylor"

\end_inset

 we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxReorg"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{1}-J_{2}=-\left(\frac{\partial J}{\partial x}\right)\varDelta x\label{eq:FluxReorg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inserting the right side of this equation in place of 
\begin_inset Formula $(J_{1}-J_{2})$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxConcChg"

\end_inset

 and canceling the 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta x$
\end_inset

 terms on both sides of the resulting equation yields equation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\left(\frac{\partial J}{\partial x}\right)\delta t=\delta c\label{eq:FluxInterm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the limit that the increments (
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta c$
\end_inset

) go to zero, it follows that equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FluxInterm"

\end_inset

 can be expressed as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FicksSimple"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\partial c}{\partial t}\right)=-\left(\frac{\partial J}{\partial x}\right)\label{eq:FicksSimple}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, we know from Fick's First Law that 
\begin_inset Formula $J=-D(\partial c/\partial x)$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $-D(\partial c/\partial x)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:FicksSimple"

\end_inset

, we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ficks2ndGen"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\partial c}{\partial t}\right)=\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(D\frac{\partial c}{\partial x}\right)\label{eq:Ficks2ndGen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the most general form of Fick's Second Law, which holds for all
 situations, including those in which the diffusion coefficient is a function
 of composition (and therefore position).
 Fortunately, in many situations the diffusion coefficient does not vary
 significantly over the concentration range involved and therefore does
 not change significantly with position.
 This simplifies things considerably.
 Fick's Second Law of diffusion becomes equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ficks2nd"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\partial c}{\partial t}\right)=D\left(\frac{\partial^{2}c}{\partial x^{2}}\right)\label{eq:Ficks2nd}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation tells us that the rate of change of concentration at a given
 point is proportional (by the diffusion coefficient) to the second derivative
 of concentration with respect to distance at that point.
 We can use this equation to 1) ascertain whether the concentration of an
 impurity is increasing or decreasing with time at a chosen point, given
 a specific concentration profile, and 2) to test whether specific diffusion
 equations are valid, namely that all such equations must obey Fick's Second
 Law as expressed in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ficks2nd"

\end_inset

 (see the following section).
 As an illustration of the first application, consider the three concentration
 profiles in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ThreeProfiles"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/ThreeProfiles.svg
	scale 75

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Analysis of three concentration profiles by Fick's Second Law.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:ThreeProfiles"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The concave-up concentration profile on the left has a second derivative
 of concentration with respect to distance that is everywhere positive.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\partial c/\partial t)$
\end_inset

 must be positive; concentration is increasing with time as shown by the
 vertical double-arrow.
 The linear concentration profile in the middle plot has a second derivative
 with respect to distance that is zero.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\partial c/\partial t)$
\end_inset

 is zero; local concentration is not changing with time.
 This is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

steady-state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 situation discussed in the previous section.
 The concave-down concentration profile on the right has a second derivative
 of concentration with respect to distance that is everywhere negative.
 This means the 
\begin_inset Formula $(\partial c/\partial t)$
\end_inset

 is everywhere negative; concentration is decreasing with time as shown
 by the vertical double-arrow.
\end_layout

