\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sinusoidal composition profile.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SineWave"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At time zero we can express the concentration profile as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SineZerotime"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c(x,0)=\bar{c}+\beta(0)sin\left(\frac{\pi x}{l}\right)\label{eq:SineZerotime}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(0)$
\end_inset

 is the amplitude of the sine wave at time zero.
 If we allow diffusion to proceed, the concentration profile will relax
 as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SineWave"

\end_inset

.
 It turns out that the solution to Fick's Second Law for these boundary
 conditions is given by equation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c(x,t)=\bar{c}+\beta(0)sin\left(\frac{\pi x}{l}\right)\exp\left(-\frac{Dt\pi^{2}}{l^{2}}\right)\label{eq:SineEqn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can prove to yourself that this equation is a solution to Fick's Second
 Law by taking the first derivative with respect to time 
\begin_inset Formula $(t)$
\end_inset

 and comparing the result with the second derivative with respect to distance
 
\begin_inset Formula $(x)$
\end_inset

.
 The two derivatives should be identical.
 Let's test this equation by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

.
 This simply reverts to the time zero function in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SineZerotime"

\end_inset

.
 Now let's consider the variation of composition at the point, 
\begin_inset Formula $x=l/2$
\end_inset

.
 Since the sine of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pi(l/2)/l)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/2$
\end_inset

 is unity, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SineEqn"

\end_inset

 becomes equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Sinelby2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c(\frac{l}{2},t)-\bar{c}=\beta(0)\exp\left(-\frac{Dt\pi^{2}}{l^{2}}\right)=\beta(0)\exp\left(-\frac{t}{\tau}\right)\label{eq:Sinelby2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, is referred to as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

relaxation time,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and is given by equation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau=\frac{l^{2}}{\pi^{2}D}\label{eq:RelaxTime}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When time is equal to the relaxation time 
\begin_inset Formula $(t=\tau)$
\end_inset

 the amplitude above the average composition at the point, 
\begin_inset Formula $x=l/2$
\end_inset

, according to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Sinelby2"

\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(0)/e$
\end_inset

 or 0.368
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(0).$
\end_inset

 This will, in fact, be true of every point along the profile; each composition
 will be 36.8% of its value at time equal to zero, as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:RelaxTime"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

