\begin_layout Subsection
Non-Infinite Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Non-infinite systems
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are those where concentration profiles span the entire specimen, from one
 end to the other.
 Or if diffusion is taking place from both sides of a plate or slab, the
 two concentration profiles overlap in the middle of the specimen.
 A classic example is diffusion out of a slab.
 For example, in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SlabDiff"

\end_inset

 a slab of thickness, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, with initial impurity concentration, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{o}$
\end_inset

, is held in an environment that takes the surface concentration, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}$
\end_inset

, to zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SlabDiff.svg
	lyxscale 40
	scale 70

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Diffusion of an impurity out of a slab.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SlabDiff"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At short times the diffusion profiles do not overlap.
 They are described by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

semi-infinite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 solutions to Fick's Second Law, as will be described in the following section.
 At longer times, however, the diffusion profiles do overlap.
 The solution to Fick's Second Law for this situation is complicated, as
 shown in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NonInfiniteGen"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c(x,t)=\frac{4c_{o}}{\pi}\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\left(\frac{1}{2j+1}\right)sin\frac{(2j+1)\pi x}{h}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{(2j+1)\pi}{h}\right)^{2}Dt\right]\label{eq:NonInfiniteGen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fortunately, the first term dominates, giving us equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NonInfinite1st"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c(x,t)=\frac{4c_{o}}{\pi}sin(\frac{\pi x}{h})\exp\left(-\frac{Dt\pi^{2}}{h^{2}}\right)\label{eq:NonInfinite1st}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation would be used if one wanted to estimate a composition at a
 specific point and time.
 More often, however, we are interested in the average composition in the
 overall slab, as shown in the diagram on the right side of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SlabDiff"

\end_inset

.
 This is found by integrating equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NonInfiniteGen"

\end_inset

 to obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AverageComp1st"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{c}(t)=\frac{1}{h}\int_{0}^{h}c(x,t)dx=\frac{8c_{o}}{\pi^{2}}\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(2j+1)^{2}}\exp\left[-\left(\frac{(2j+1)\pi}{h}\right)^{2}Dt\right]\label{eq:AverageComp1st}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, fortunately, the first term dominates, and for average compositions
 less than 80% of the initial composition (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}\leq0.8c_{o}$
\end_inset

) the first term is an excellent approximation to the solution.
 The results in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AverageComp"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\bar{c}}{c_{o}}=\frac{8}{\pi^{2}}\exp(-\frac{t}{\tau})\label{eq:AverageComp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=h^{2}/\pi^{2}D$
\end_inset

 is called the relaxation time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AverageComp"

\end_inset

 is very useful for describing the degassing of metals, including decarburizatio
n of steels.
 In this case the diffusion coefficient in the relaxation time would be
 that of the particular gas species or of carbon in the particular metal.
 Another application involves the relaxation of vacancies in a supersaturated
 metal, for example a metal quenched from high temperature has a large vacancy
 population.
 If the metal is taken to an intermediate temperature where the equilibrium
 vacancy concentration is small (effectively zero compared to the quenched-in
 concentration, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{o}$
\end_inset

) and vacancies are sufficiently mobile that they can annihilate at sinks
 such as dislocation cores or grain boundaries, relaxation will occur.
 The situation involving dislocation cores is represented schematically
 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DislRelax"

\end_inset

, where the concentration of vacancies is shown during relaxation from the
 initial, quenched-in concentration, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{o}$
\end_inset

, to a point where the average vacancy concentration is 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 would be the average dislocation spacing and the diffusion coefficient
 would be that of vacancies in the metal of interest.
\end_layout

