	filename figures/TracerDiff2.svg
	lyxscale 45
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Schematic of the serial sectioning process, and how the tracer diffusion
 coefficient is determined.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SerialSection"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sectioning is typically accomplished using the same grinding media (abrasive
 cloths, powders) used for metallographic sample preparation.
 It is very important, however, to quantify both the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

depth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 removed (each 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta x$
\end_inset

 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SerialSection"

\end_inset

) and the tracer concentration (
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SerialSection"

\end_inset

) for each section.
 Alternatively, the count rate (counts/time) can be measured by a radiation
 detector.
 The count rate will be directly proportional to the concentration in each
 section.
 The increment of depth can be measured directly by a high precision micro-calip
er.
 Alternatively, it can be indirectly calculated from the mass removed, which
 can be measured quite accurately.
 In the case of non-radioactive tracers, mass spectrometry is employed to
 calculate the tracer content in a given section.
 With a radioactive tracer, the abrasive cloth holding the powder of the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

section
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 removed can be placed in a radiation detector and counted for a predetermined
 time period.
 The solution to Fick's Second Law that reflects the boundary conditions
 for thin film tracer diffusion is given in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ThinFilmTracer"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C=\frac{M}{2\sqrt{\pi Dt}}\exp\left(\frac{-x^{2}}{4Dt}\right)\label{eq:ThinFilmTracer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is either the tracer concentration or the tracer's radioactive count rate,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the area concentration of tracer deposited on the surface of crystal
 #1 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TracerDiff"

\end_inset

.
 Taking the natural logarithm of both sides of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ThinFilmTracer"

\end_inset

 gives equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:LnThinFilm"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln C=\ln\left(\frac{M}{2\sqrt{\pi Dt}}\right)-\frac{x^{2}}{4Dt}\label{eq:LnThinFilm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The slope of a plot of the natural logarithm of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/4D^{*}t$
\end_inset

, as depicted on the right side of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SerialSection"

\end_inset

.
 Since the diffusion time is known, the diffusion coefficient can be calculated.
 This process is repeated at other temperatures in order to establish the
 pre-exponential factor (
\begin_inset Formula $D_{o}$
\end_inset

) and activation energy (
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

) of the tracer diffusion coefficient (
\begin_inset Formula $D^{*}$
\end_inset

) as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:TracerArrhenius"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D^{*}=D_{o}\exp\left(-\frac{Q}{RT}\right)\label{eq:TracerArrhenius}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{o}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pre-exponential factor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is the activation energy of diffusion.
 We discuss the origin(s) of this characteristic of diffusion vs.
 temperature behavior (so-called Arrhenius behavior) in a later section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Constant Surface Composition Situations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As opposed to thin film tracer diffusion, where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

surface
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 composition diminishes with time, there are a number of situations in materials
 science and engineering where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

surface
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 composition is maintained constant with time.
 These include 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

doping
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 situations, where a solid is held in an atmosphere that keeps the composition
 of an impurity at a constant level on the exposed surface.
 Similarly, the carburization of iron or steel can be controlled by holding
 the surface in an atmosphere with a fixed ratio of carbon monoxide and
 carbon dioxide.
 The amount of carbon in solution at the surface is thereby fixed according
 to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:carburization"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
2CO(gas)\Leftrightarrow CO_{2}(gas)+\bar{C}(insolution)\label{eq:carburization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As carbon diffuses into the interior of the solid, the above reaction guarantees
 that additional carbon is added to the surface to maintain the surface
 carbon composition.
 The overall impurity (or carbon) content of the solid is given by equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ConstSurfIntegral"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{tot}=A\int_{0}^{\infty}c(x)dx\label{eq:ConstSurfIntegral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where A is the area of the surface into which solute is diffusing.
 This means, of course, that as opposed to thin film tracer diffusion, the
 overall solute content steadily increases with time.
 This is shown schematically on the left side of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TwoLevelDiffVsTime"

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{o}$
\end_inset

 is the initial carbon content and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the surface composition.
 The concentration profile moves progressively to the right with time, as
 the interior of the solid is progressively enriched with solute.
 We later consider how thick the sample must be to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

semi-infinite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 compared to the diffusion profile, but from Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TwoLevelDiffVsTime"

\end_inset

 it follows that the sample dimension should be large relative to the diffusion
 profile at the longest time applied.
\end_layout

