\begin_layout Standard
Before we introduce the solution to Fick's Second Law that meets the boundary
 conditions of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TwoLevelDiffVsTime"

\end_inset

, we will make the simplifying assumption that the diffusion coefficient
 does not vary with impurity content, and therefore distance from the surface
 (
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

).
 This is valid for the doping of semiconductors from gas phase precursors,
 where relatively small dopant levels are involved.
 However, in the case of carburization, relatively large changes in solute
 (carbon) content occur and the diffusion coefficient is known to vary somewhat
 with carbon composition (and therefore position) along the diffusion profile.
 Fortunately, relatively good predictions of carbon diffusion profiles can
 be obtained by employing an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

average
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 carbon diffusion coefficient (discussed later) that can be assumed invariant
 with carbon content (and position).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to Fick's Second Law corresponding to the boundary conditions
 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TwoLevelDiffVsTime"

\end_inset

 is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:erfCarb2level"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c(x,t)=c_{s}-(c_{s}-c_{o})erf\left(\frac{x}{2\sqrt{Dt}}\right)\label{eq:erfCarb2level}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is usually written as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:erfCarb2level2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{c_{s}-c(x,t)}{c_{s}-c_{o}}=erf\left(\frac{x}{2\sqrt{Dt}}\right)\label{eq:erfCarb2level2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the distance from the surface, 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the diffusion coefficient (a constant diffusion temperature is assumed),
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the time period over which diffusion takes place.
 You should have encountered the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

error function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $erf$
\end_inset

) in prior math courses.
 It is an indefinite integral of the form in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IndefIntegral"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
erf(z)=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\int_{0}^{z}e^{-\eta^{2}}d\eta\label{eq:IndefIntegral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is known as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dummy variable.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 In our case, 
\begin_inset Formula $z=x/(2\sqrt{Dt})$
\end_inset

.
 In days past, with no closed-form solution to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:IndefIntegral"

\end_inset

, one resorted to tables of the error function.
 Fortunately, many modern calculators now include the error function.
 Alternatively, there have been many mathematical approximations.
 The most straightforward amongst the collection in the Handbook of Mathematical
 Functions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "abramowitz_handbook_1965"

\end_inset

, having a reported accuracy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm5x10^{-4}$
\end_inset

, is equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CompErfApprox"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1-erf(z)=erfc(z)\approx(1+a_{1}z+a_{2}z^{2}+a_{3}z^{3}+a_{4}z^{4})^{-4}\label{eq:CompErfApprox}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=0.278393$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}=0.230389$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{3}=0.000972$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{4}=0.078108$
\end_inset

.
 This approximation can be used in a either a computer program or in a mathemati
cal spreadsheet to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $erf(z)$
\end_inset

.
 In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CompErfApprox"

\end_inset

 we have also introduced the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

complementary error function,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $erfc(z)$
\end_inset

.
 The simple relationship between the two functions in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ErfcAndErf"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
erfc(z)=1-erf(z)\label{eq:ErfcAndErf}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is illustrated in Figure 
