\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 that has an error function value of 0.5 is very close to 0.5 (see the error
 function Table or Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ErfAndEfrcPlot"

\end_inset

), or more precisely 
\begin_inset Formula $z=x/\sqrt{Dt}=0.477$
\end_inset

.
 If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx0.5$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0.5}\approx\sqrt{Dt}$
\end_inset

.
 This distance of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

root Dt
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is commonly referred to as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion depth.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 It is a useful 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

metric
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for diffusion in situations involving constant surface composition.
 For example, one might ask, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

How much longer must I diffuse at the same temperature to double the diffusion
 depth?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The answer follows from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0.5}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DblDepthQuadTime"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{x_{0.5}^{'}}{x_{0.5}}=2=\frac{\sqrt{Dt^{\prime}}}{\sqrt{Dt}}=\sqrt{\frac{t^{\prime}}{t}};\frac{t^{\prime}}{t}=4\label{eq:DblDepthQuadTime}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or four times the length of time.
 We can also establish the thickness of sample required to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

semi-infinite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with respect to a given combination of diffusion coefficient and time.
 From the previous Table of error function values, we can observe that at
 
\begin_inset Formula $z=x/\sqrt{Dt}=2$
\end_inset

 the diffusion profile has diminished by 99.5% toward the original composition.
 In other words, very little (0.5%) impurity has been delivered at this point
 in the diffusion profile.
 For diffusion from one side, a specimen must therefore be greater than
 
\begin_inset Formula $2\sqrt{Dt},$
\end_inset

 or twice the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion depth.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 For diffusion from both sides of a plate we might define 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

semi-infinite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as being 
\begin_inset Formula $>4\sqrt{Dt}$
\end_inset

 or roughly four times the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion depth.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Of course, this is arbitrary and more stringent definitions of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

semi-infinite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can be made (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $z=2.5$
\end_inset

, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $erf(z)=0.9996$
\end_inset

).
 For diffusion from both sides of a plate, this would amount to 0.08% added
 impurity at the middle of the specimen.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, we should not forget our non-infinite solutions to Fick's Second
 Law, which are required in place of error function (semi-infinite) solutions
 when there is significant overlap of diffusion profiles from the two sides
 of a plate.
 Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NonInfiniteGen"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NonInfinite1st"

\end_inset

 would be used to determine the concentration at a given position, whereas
 equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AverageComp1st"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AverageComp"

\end_inset

 would be employed to determine the average composition (above the initial
 composition) for the plate.
 We revisit such overlap when we consider decarburization (below).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the solutions that follow are simply permutations of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:erfCarb2level2"

\end_inset

.
 For instance, let's consider carburization or doping of an initially 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 host.
 Of course, from thermodynamics we know that there is no such thing as complete
 purity.
 Impurities, including the one we are interested in, are always present
 to some degree.
 However, their level can be considered so inconsequential as to be effectively
 zero, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{o}$
\end_inset

 can be taken to be zero in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:erfCarb2level2"

\end_inset

.
 By making this assumption and rearranging, we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CarbPure"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

