\begin_layout Subsection
Interstitial Diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although self-diffusion by interstitials is possible in certain ceramic
 materials, we will restrict our consideration to impurity diffusion where
 the impurity spends all of its time in the interstices of the crystal lattice.
 A good example is carbon diffusion in iron.
 This type of impurity diffusion has special requirements, namely that 1)
 the atomic radius of the impurity is significantly less than that of the
 host (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{C}<r_{Fe}$
\end_inset

), and 2) the atomic radius of the impurity is comparable to that of the
 interstices.
 It should be stressed that self-diffusion in close-packed metals never
 takes place by interstitial diffusion.
 The radius of a host atom is far too great for it to squeeze into the much
 smaller interstices in between host atoms.
 To place a host atom into such an interstice would be highly unfavorable
 energetically; self-interstitials are therefore highly unlikely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's begin to analyze interstitial diffusion using the modular plug-in
 chart in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

.
 Since the interstitial is always an interstitial, there is no thermal activatio
n process associated with its formation as in Box D.
 Furthermore, the availability factor for interstitial jumps can be assumed
 to be essentially unity (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{int}\approx1$
\end_inset

), namely adjacent interstitial sites into which the interstitial can jump
 can be assumed to be empty.
 Of course, at the highest carbon contents there is a finite possibility
 that an adjacent interstitial is occupied.
 We could express the availability factor as (
\begin_inset Formula $1-X_{i}$
\end_inset

), where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the site fraction of carbon interstitials.
 But for simplicity we will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\ll1$
\end_inset

 and assume an availability factor (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{int}$
\end_inset

) of unity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is time to add important functions to our diffusion 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

toolkit.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 These have to do with the defect jump frequency in Box C of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

.
 In moving from one interstitial site to another, a certain amount of lattice
 dilation must occur, as illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:InterstMotionEnergy"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

