\begin_layout Standard
In other words, adjacent atoms must move apart to enable the interstitial
 to pass.
 Energetically, this amounts to surpassing an energy barrier that separates
 the two sites.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:InterstMotionEnergy"

\end_inset

 illustrates the special configuration with the interstitial at the so-called
 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

saddle-point
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Saddle-point
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The energy landscape is shaped like a saddle.
 Alternately, you can think about a mountain pass.
 You go up and over the pass, but when you are at the top of the pass you
 find the land rising to either side.
 From statistical mechanics, the probability that an interstitial has sufficient
 energy to reach the saddle point is small.
 It is governed by the height of the pass (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta G_{m}$
\end_inset

) and the temperature.
 Higher temperature means more energy being available to the interstitials,
 and an increasing fraction of them having the probability to make it to/past
 the saddle point.
 The relationship is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SaddleProb"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
probability\propto\exp\left(\frac{-\varDelta G_{m}}{RT}\right)\label{eq:SaddleProb}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We refer to 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta G_{m}$
\end_inset

 as the free energy of motion which, in turn, can be separated into enthalpy
 of motion (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{m}$
\end_inset

) and entropy of motion (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta S_{m}$
\end_inset

) components as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MotionGHS"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta G_{m}=\varDelta H_{m}-T\varDelta S_{m}\label{eq:MotionGHS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be apparent that an interstitial at the saddle point has a different
 entropy.
 Certainly, its vibrational frequency, and thus its vibrational entropy,
 should be different at the dilated/congested saddle than in either interstice,
 i.e., the energy wells on either side of the energy barrier in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:InterstMotionEnergy"

\end_inset

.
 We can use the information in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MotionGHS"

\end_inset

 to arrive at the equation in Box C of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

, or equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:InterstJumpFreq"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varGamma_{i}=z\nu\exp\left(\frac{\varDelta S_{mi}}{R}\right)\exp\left(\frac{-\varDelta H_{mi}}{RT}\right)\label{eq:InterstJumpFreq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we have replaced 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{def}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 for interstitial), and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta S_{mi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{mi}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta S_{def}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{def}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 The other constants are 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, the attempt frequency, and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, the coordination number of how many empty interstitial sites surround
 an occupied interstitial site.
 The attempt frequency can be assumed to be the lattice vibrational frequency,
 on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}$
\end_inset

 per second.
 You probably encountered the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Debye frequency
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in your prior materials thermodynamics work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plugging 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{i}$
\end_inset

 from equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{def}$
\end_inset

 in Boxes C and B and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{def}$
\end_inset

 in Boxes D and B of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

, we obtain the following equation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=\left[\frac{1}{6}\alpha^{2}z\nu\exp\left(\frac{\varDelta S_{mi}}{R}\right)\right]\exp\left(\frac{-\varDelta H_{mi}}{RT}\right)\label{eq:DiffInterst1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we consider A to be the host lattice and B to be the species moving via
 interstices, we can simplify equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffInterst1"

\end_inset

 to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffInterst2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{B}=D_{Bo}\exp\left(\frac{-Q_{I}}{R}\right)\label{eq:DiffInterst2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{Bo}$
\end_inset

 is the pre-exponential factor for impurity diffusion of species B by interstiti
al mechanism, which includes all the entities within the brackets of equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffInterst1"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{I}$
\end_inset

 is the activation energy for interstitial motion.
 Since there is no defect formation energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{I}$
\end_inset

 is the same as the enthalpy of motion or 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{mi}$
\end_inset

.
 Before we take a try at predicting pre-exponential factors for interstitial
 diffusion, let's rearrange equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffInterst2"

\end_inset

 to separate out geometric (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

) and entropic (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) factors, as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffInterst3"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=\gamma SE_{act}=\left(\frac{\alpha^{2}z\nu}{6}\right)\left(\exp\frac{\varDelta S_{mi}}{R}\right)\exp\left(\frac{-\varDelta H_{mi}}{RT}\right)\label{eq:DiffInterst3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's first unpack the underlying parameters in the geometric factor (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

).
 We already know that the attempt frequency (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

) is on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}/s$
\end_inset

.
 But the jump distance (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

) and coordination number (
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

) depend upon not only the crystal structure, but upon the actual element/metal
 under consideration.
 Let's focus our concentration on iron in both fcc (austenite) and bcc (ferrite)
 forms, and consider the case of the interstitial diffusion of carbon.
 The two crystal structures are displayed in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CarbonJumpAustFerr"

\end_inset

.
 More importantly, the interstitial positions are marked with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

X's.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 In addition, a typical jump distance is shown by an arrow for each structure.
\end_layout

