\begin_layout Standard
Let's first consider carbon diffusion in fcc-Fe (austenite), whose structure
 is shown on the left side of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CarbonJumpAustFerr"

\end_inset

.
 It is obvious that the two sets of lattice positions (host atoms, interstices)
 form interpenetrating fcc lattices.
 In fact, we will encounter interpenetrating lattices when we consider the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rocksalt
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 structure of sodium chloride or table salt (NaCl), where the electropositive
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Na^{+}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sit on one set of sites and the electronegative 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Cl^{-}}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

anions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sit on the other.
 In austenite, most of the second interpenetrating (interstitial) lattice
 is empty.
 However, the fact that it (the interstitial lattice) is also fcc is quite
 important.
 It means that the coordination number of empty interstitials sites around
 any given occupied interstitial site will be the same as the coordination
 number of neighboring iron atoms around any given iron host atom.
 This gives us the value we need for the coordination number in 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffInterst3"

\end_inset

, namely 12.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the jump distance (or the arrow length in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CarbonJumpAustFerr"

\end_inset

) is the same as the distance between close-packed atoms (see the lower
 diagram in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CarbonJumpAustFerr"

\end_inset

), or one-half of the face-diagonal 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sqrt{2}a_{o}/2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Since the lattice parameter (
\begin_inset Formula $a_{o}$
\end_inset

) of fcc iron is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 0.37 nm.
 the jump distance would be 8
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.26$
\end_inset

 nm.
 Diffusion coefficients are rarely given in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{nm^{2}/s}$
\end_inset

, however.
 So let's convert 0.26 nm to centimeters, or 
\begin_inset Formula $2.6x10^{-8}\,\mathrm{cm}$
\end_inset

.
 This yields the following for the geometric factor for diffusion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma=\mathrm{z\Gamma\alpha^{2}/6=12\left(10^{13}\,s^{-1}\right)\left(2.6x10^{-8}\,cm\right)^{2}/6=0.014\,cm^{2}/s}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There have been several estimates of the entropic term (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffInterst3"

\end_inset

.
 One of the most straightforward calculations took into account the elastic
 strain associated with the saddle point (C.
 Zener in Imperfections in Nearly Perfect Crystals, 1952, p.289) and also
 the change in vibrational entropy associated with the saddle point 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "huntington_calculation_1955"

\end_inset

, arriving at the result that the entropy of interstitial motion was 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta S_{mi}\approx R$
\end_inset

, such that the entropic term (
\begin_inset Formula $S=\exp\left(\varDelta S_{mi}/RT\right)$
\end_inset

) was approximately 2.7.
 The product of the geometric factor (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

) and the entropic factor (S) in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffInterst3"

\end_inset

 is the pre-exponential coefficient of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffInterst2"

\end_inset

.
 Based upon our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

back of the envelope
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 calculations, we predict a value for 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{Bo}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.38\,\mathrm{cm^{2}/s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we make a comparison with experimental values, it must be stressed
 that owing to the larger interstice size in fcc iron vs.
 bcc iron, the former (austenite) can incorporate a much larger carbon content
 than the latter (ferrite).
 We mentioned previously that the diffusion of carbon in fcc iron was not
 a constant, but rather varied measurably with carbon content.
 Fortunately, the variation is not extreme and a practicable composition-indepen
dent approximation appears in most diffusion textbooks.
 This approximation is given by the following equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CarbDiffAustApprox"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{D}_{C}(\mathrm{austenite})\approx0.2\mathrm{\frac{cm^{2}}{s}}\exp\left(\frac{-138\mathrm{kJ/mole}}{\mathrm{RT}}\right)\label{eq:CarbDiffAustApprox}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given our rather simplistic assumptions and the fact that the experimental
 equation is itself an approximation, the agreement of pre-exponential values
 (estimated: 
\begin_inset Formula $0.38\,\mathrm{cm^{2}/s}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 experimental: 
\begin_inset Formula $0.2\,\mathrm{cm^{2}/s}$
\end_inset

) is remarkable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's see how we do estimating the geometric factor and pre-exponent for
 carbon diffusion in the bcc (ferrite) form of iron.
 Interestingly, the interstices in bcc iron exist only on the faces of the
 unit cell as shown on the right side of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CarbonJumpAustFerr"

\end_inset

.
 These interstices are found along the edges and at the face centers of
 the unit cell.
 As a result, the jump distance is half of the cube edge or lattice parameter,
 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=a_{o}/2=0.29nm/2=0.14nm$
\end_inset

.
 Since there are no bcc interstices within the unit cell, the coordination
 number can be determined by looking at the face-centered interstice on
 any face in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CarbonJumpAustFerr"

\end_inset

.
 If occupied, it is surrounded by 4 empty interstices at the 4 cube edge
 positions, so 
\begin_inset Formula $z=4$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming once again an attempt frequency of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10^{13}/s$
\end_inset

, we arrive at a geometric factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx0.0013cm^{2}/s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once again, there have been several estimates of the entropic term (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffInterst3"

\end_inset

.
 If we assume, as with the fcc structure, that the entropy of interstitial
 motion is 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta S_{mi}\approx R$
\end_inset

 such that the entropic term of 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\exp\left(\varDelta S_{mi}/RT\right)$
\end_inset

 is approximately 2.7, we arrive at a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

back of the envelope
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 estimate for 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{Bo}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim3.5x10^{-3}\,\mathrm{cm^{2}/s}$
\end_inset

.
 The experimental equation for carbon diffusion in bcc iron is 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wert_diffusion_1950"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{C}(\mathrm{ferrite})=2.0x10^{-2}\mathrm{cm^{2}/s}\exp\left(\frac{-84.1\mathrm{kJ/mole}}{RT}\right)\label{eq:CarbDiffFerrite}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This time there is only agreement of pre-exponent within an order of magnitude,
 however this can be considered quite good considering all the approximations
 we have made.
 As additional support for our atomistic approach, the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{Bo}$
\end_inset

 values are 
\begin_inset Formula $3.0x10^{-3}\mathrm{\,cm^{2}/s}$
\end_inset

 for nitrogen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wert_measurements_1950"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1.0x10^{-3}\,\mathrm{cm^{2}/s}$
\end_inset

 for hydrogen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "johnson_diffusivity_????"

\end_inset

, in quite satisfactory agreement with our prediction.
 The corresponding enthalpies of motion (
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{I}$
\end_inset

) are 
\begin_inset Formula $76.1\,\mathrm{kJ/mole}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $13.4\,\mathrm{kJ/mole}$
\end_inset

 for N 
