\begin_layout Standard
Substitutional impurities, namely those that sit on host atom sites rather
 than in its interstices, also depend upon vacancy motion for diffusion
 to take place.
 The shaded atom in the bottom-right configuration in Figure Z represents
 such a substitutional impurity.
 It is obvious that for this to take place, the atomic radius of the impurity
 must be comparable to that of the host.
 Impurity atoms will similarly bide their time waiting to exchange with
 a host vacancy that comes their way.
 They may exchange more readily or less so than the host atoms, but both
 diffuse by so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

vacancy mechanism.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider vacancy diffusion within the rubric of the modular 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

plug-in
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 diagram of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

.
 Box B of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

 will become equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacDiffJumpFreq"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varGamma=\varGamma_{v}X_{v}\label{eq:VacDiffJumpFreq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{v}$
\end_inset

 is the vacancy jump frequency and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{v}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

availability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 factor or site fraction of vacancies.
 The latter amounts to the probability that each adjacent site is unoccupied.
 The first of these two terms can be derived by analogy to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:InterstJumpFreq"

\end_inset

 for interstitial motion, or equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacJumpFreq"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varGamma_{v}=z\nu\exp\left(\frac{\varDelta S_{mv}}{RT}\right)\exp\left(\frac{-\varDelta H_{mv}}{RT}\right)\label{eq:VacJumpFreq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is the coordination number, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is the attempt frequency, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta S_{mv}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{mv}$
\end_inset

 are the entropy and enthalpy of vacancy motion, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will address each of these parameters later, but for now let's concentrate
 on the site fraction of vacancies or 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 If temperature is sufficiently high, the vacancy concentration will be
 in thermodynamic equilibrium.
 We can approach this problem as was done for the regular solution model
 in your prior thermodynamics coursework.
 Expressions were written for both the enthalpy of mixing in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSolnH"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta H^{M}=\Omega X_{A}X_{B}\label{eq:RegSolnH}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the entropy of mixing in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSolnS"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-T\varDelta S^{M}=-T\left[-R(X_{A}\ln X_{A}+X_{B}\ln X_{B})\right]\label{eq:RegSolnS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

interaction parameter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}$
\end_inset

 represent the mole fractions of the two components.
 The phase boundaries of the regular solution solvus were found by plugging
 these two equations into the overall expression for the free energy of
 mixing, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSolnG"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta G^{M}=\varDelta H^{M}-T\varDelta S^{M}\label{eq:RegSolnG}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
taking the derivative with respect to composition (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{B}$
\end_inset

), and setting the result equal to zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of the formation of vacancies in a solid metal, the corresponding
 enthalpy term is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacFormH"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta H\simeq X_{v}\varDelta H_{v}\label{eq:VacFormH}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{v}$
\end_inset

 represents the enthalpy increase per mole of vacancies.
 Similarly, the entropy of forming a mole of vacancies is given by equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacFormS"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta S=\varDelta S_{nonconfig}+\varDelta S_{config}\label{eq:VacFormS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the non-configurational entropy, incorporating the thermal/vibrational
 entropy per mole of vacancies (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta S_{v}$
\end_inset

), is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacFormSVibr"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta S_{nonconfig}\simeq X_{v}\varDelta S_{v}\label{eq:VacFormSVibr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the configurational entropy looks a lot like the entropy of mixing (in
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RegSolnS"

\end_inset

) or equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacFormSMix"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta S_{config}=-R[X\ln X_{v}+(1-X_{v})\ln(1-X_{v})]\label{eq:VacFormSMix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we begin with the standard free energy of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

perfect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 crystal (
\begin_inset Formula $G_{A}^{o}$
\end_inset

), and insert all the enthalpic and entropic terms for vacancy formation,
 the Gibbs free energy of the defective crystal compared to that of the
 perfect crystal is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacFormTot"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{A}-G_{A}^{o}=\varDelta G_{v}=X_{v}\varDelta H_{v}-TX_{v}\varDelta S_{v}+RT\left[X_{v}\ln X_{v}+(1-X_{v})\ln(1-X_{v})\right]\label{eq:VacFormTot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

