\begin_layout Standard
At first, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta G_{v}$
\end_inset

 decreases with increasing vacancy concentration, being dominated by the
 entropy terms.
 Eventually, however, the enthalpy term turns things around, dominating
 at higher vacancy concentrations.
 A minimum in the free energy of vacancy formation occurs at the so-called
 equilibrium value (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{v}^{e}$
\end_inset

).
 This value can be derived by taking the first derivative of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacFormTot"

\end_inset

 and setting it equation to zero as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacFormDeriv"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\frac{\partial G}{\partial X_{v}}\right)_{X_{v}=X_{v}^{e}}=0=\varDelta H_{v}-T\varDelta S_{v}+RT\ln\left(\frac{X_{v}^{e}}{1-X_{v}^{e}}\right)\label{eq:VacFormDeriv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rearranging equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacFormDeriv"

\end_inset

, exponentiating, and making the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{v}^{e}\ll1$
\end_inset

, we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SiteFracVacs"

\end_inset

, which relates the equilibrium vacancy concentration (site fraction of
 vacancies) to temperature:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{v}^{e}=\exp\left(\frac{\varDelta S_{v}}{R}\right)\exp\left(\frac{-\varDelta H_{v}}{RT}\right)\label{eq:SiteFracVacs}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For now, let's leave the testing of our assumption (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{v}^{e}\ll1$
\end_inset

) for later, and plug this equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SiteFracVacs"

\end_inset

) into Box D of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

.
 We previously derived equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacJumpFreq"

\end_inset

, which is Box C of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

.
 Plugging these equations into the jump frequency expression of Box B, we
 obtain an overall equation for self-diffusion (Box A) by vacancy mechanism,
 or equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfDiffOverall"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{A}=\left[\frac{1}{6}\alpha^{2}z\nu\exp\left(\frac{\varDelta S_{v}+\varDelta S_{mv}}{R}\right)\right]\exp\left[\frac{-(\varDelta H_{v}+\varDelta H_{mv})}{RT}\right]\label{eq:SelfDiffOverall}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which can be simplified to the basic equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfDiffBasic"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{A}=D_{Ao}\exp\left(\frac{-Q_{SD}}{RT}\right)\label{eq:SelfDiffBasic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{SD}$
\end_inset

, the activation energy of self-diffusion, is the sum of formation (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{v}$
\end_inset

) and motion (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{mv}$
\end_inset

) enthalpies, and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{Ao}$
\end_inset

 is the pre-exponential factor that incorporates all the factors within
 the first bracket of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfDiffOverall"

\end_inset

.
 As with interstitial diffusion, we can reorganize equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfDiffOverall"

\end_inset

 into geometric (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

), entropic (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

), and activation energy (
\begin_inset Formula $E_{act}$
\end_inset

) factors, as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacDiffThreeTerm"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{A}=\gamma SE_{act}=\left(\frac{\alpha^{2}z\nu}{6}\right)\left[\exp\left(\frac{\varDelta S_{v}+\varDelta S_{mv}}{R}\right)\right]\left[\exp\left(\frac{-(\varDelta H_{v}+\varDelta H_{mv})}{RT}\right)\right]\label{eq:VacDiffThreeTerm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we examine the factors in the pre-exponent and estimate its value,
 it is useful to calculate the diffusion coefficient of the vacancies themselves.
 Plugging equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacJumpFreq"

\end_inset

 into Box C of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

 and inserting this for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma$
\end_inset

 term in Box A, we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacDiffCoeff"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{v}=\frac{1}{6}\alpha^{2}\varGamma_{v}=\left[\frac{1}{6}z\nu\alpha^{2}\exp\left(\frac{\varDelta S_{mv}}{R}\right)\right]\exp\left(\frac{-\varDelta H_{mv}}{RT}\right)\label{eq:VacDiffCoeff}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfDiffOverall"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacDiffCoeff"

\end_inset

, two important relationships result, equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfVacJumpComp"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfVacDiffComp"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varGamma_{A}=\varGamma_{v}X_{v}\label{eq:SelfVacJumpComp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{A}=D_{v}X_{v}\label{eq:SelfVacDiffComp}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we said above, the vacancies are moving around much more frequently than
 individual host atoms.
 In the following section, we mention that the vacancy concentration in
 fcc metals can be as high as 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{v}\sim0.001$
\end_inset

 at just below their melting points.
 Simple math shows us that the ratio of jump frequencies (
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{v}/\varGamma_{A}$
\end_inset

) or diffusivities (
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}/D_{A}$
\end_inset

), that is of vacancies vs.
 host atoms, will therefore be 1000x! Actually, you can prove this to yourself
 by solving a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tile
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 puzzle and counting the number of jumps made by each numbered tile compared
 to the number of jumps the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

vacancy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 makes to solve the puzzle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's estimate a range of pre-exponential factors for self-diffusion
 in fcc metals based upon our best guess of atomistic factors.
 We will assume a representative value for the jump distance in equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfDiffOverall"

\end_inset

 of approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $0.3nm$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $0.3x10^{-7}cm$
\end_inset

.
