\begin_layout Subsection
Interstitialcy Diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of the three diffusion mechanisms we have thus far considered, interstitialcy
 diffusion is certainly the most unusual.
 The German word for this mechanism is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

zwischengitterstossmechanismus,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which does a far better job conveying the concept.
 The words that make up this moniker will help us understand its meaning.
 The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gitter
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to the normal lattice sites.
 The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

zwischen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

between.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 And the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

stoss
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shove.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This mechanism is exclusive to compounds with more than one sublattice.
 This is because the interstice size in metals is never big enough to accommodat
e a self-interstitial.
 However, in certain ceramic materials one species, for example the electroposit
ive cations, can be much smaller than the electronegative anions.
 And in this case the cation interstices can be large enough to accommodate
 cation self-interstitials.
 The classic example is AgBr, which readily forms Ag self-interstitials.
 But rather than moving around by interstitial mechanism, as carbon does
 in iron, a coordinated two-cation motion mechanism takes place, in which
 an interstitial cation bumps another cation off its normal site and takes
 its place.
 That's where the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shove
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 part of zwischengitterstossmechanismus comes in.
 The normal cation now becomes an interstitial cation, and the process continues.
 A schematic the first step of such a process in AgBr is shown in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:IntcyJump"

\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

before
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

after
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 positions of ions.
 Only the 
\begin_inset Formula $Ag^{+}$
\end_inset

 species are shown, since all the action involves silver cations.
\end_layout

