\begin_layout Standard
I like to think of one of two analogies for interstitialcy mechanism.
 The first involves 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sending
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 an opponent's ball in croquet.
 Once I touch your ball with mine, I have the option of positioning my ball
 under my foot right next to yours and then clobbering my ball, the transferred
 momentum sending your ball way off course.
 The other analogy involves shuffleboard (or curling, if you have ever seen
 it), where the momentum of my puck/stone is transferred to your puck, which
 (hopefully) is removed from the scoring area while mine takes its place.
 Two points need to be made about the interstitialcy event.
 As shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:IntcyJump"

\end_inset

, the process is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

collinear,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 meaning that the pushed atom moves along the same line as the pushing atom.
 This need not be the case, as we well know from the shuffleboard/curling
 analogy.
 Non-collinear interstitialcy mechanisms are definitely known to occur.
 Second, note that the interstitial has moved twice as far as the host atom
 that got pushed.
 This may not seem significant, but it is actually one way to confirm that
 the collinear interstitialcy mechanism is occurring.
 Later we will find out how to use electrical conductivity to establish
 the diffusivity by charged ions, so-called ionic diffusivity/conductivity.
 It turns out that when we measure the diffusivity of silver ions by tracer
 methods in AgBr, we get an answer that is approximately half the diffusivity
 of silver ions measured by electrical conductivity.
 Why is this? Look again at Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:IntcyJump"

\end_inset

.
 The charge (the interstitial) is moving twice as far as the shaded host
 ion (which could be a tracer ion).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the complexity of the interstitialcy mechanism and the relative dearth
 of representative pre-exponential factors, we will not subject this mechanism
 to the intense atomistic scrutiny as we did for interstitial and vacancy
 mechanisms.
 However, we can make some remarks about 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

jump frequency
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

defect availability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Box B of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

.
 It makes sense that the interstitialcy defects are jumping with a frequency,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varGamma_{iy}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $"iy"$
\end_inset

 for interstitialcy).
 But if I am a silver cation on a host site, instead of waiting for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pullers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to come along (vacancies), I am now biding my time awaiting the arrival
 of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pusher
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to come along (interstitialcy defects) and knock me on my way.
 Hence the defect availability factor will be the fraction of occupied interstic
es, or 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{iy}$
\end_inset

.
 By analogy with the vacancy mechanism, the corresponding Box E interstitialcy
 diffusion coefficient (with direct analogy to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfDiffOverall"

\end_inset

) is equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfDiffOverall-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{A}=\left[\frac{1}{6}\alpha^{2}z\nu\exp\left(\frac{\varDelta S_{iy}+\varDelta S_{miy}}{R}\right)\right]\exp\left[\frac{-(\varDelta H_{iy}+\varDelta H_{miy})}{RT}\right]\label{eq:SelfDiffOverall-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As with the vacancy mechanism, this equation has geometric (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

), entropic (
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

), and thermally-activated components (
\begin_inset Formula $E_{act}$
\end_inset

), as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacDiffThreeTerm-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{A}=\gamma SE_{act}=\left(\frac{\alpha^{2}z\nu}{6}\right)\left[\exp\left(\frac{\varDelta S_{iy}+\varDelta S_{miy}}{R}\right)\right]\left[\exp\left(\frac{-(\varDelta H_{iy}+\varDelta H_{miyv})}{RT}\right)\right]\label{eq:VacDiffThreeTerm-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The motion-related components are relatively straightforward to understand,
 however the formation components (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta S_{iy}$
\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{iy}$
\end_inset

) will have to wait until we have considered point defects in ionic solids,
 including the introduction of a special shorthand representation for ionic
 defects called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

KrÃ¶ger-Vink
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 notation.
