\begin_layout Subsection
The Arrhenius Behavior of Diffusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have shown that for all diffusion mechanisms considered thus far, Arrhenius
 behavior results, namely that the diffusion coefficient is thermally activated
 as per the equation in Box F of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DiffPlugIns"

\end_inset

.
 We already saw this behavior for tracer diffusion in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TracerDiff"

\end_inset

 and for general diffusion in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BasicDiff"

\end_inset

, which is repeated here:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=D_{o}\exp\left(\frac{-Q}{RT}\right)\label{eq:BasicDiff-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As materials scientists and engineers, we need to be confident in using
 and manipulating diffusion data that behave in this Arrhenius, thermally-activa
ted fashion.
 Here are some things we need to be able to do: 1) plot experimental data
 for diffusion on a 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln D$
\end_inset

 vs inverse temperature (T
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

) plot to extract pre-exponent and activation energy, 2) given the pre-exponent
 and activation energy for diffusion, calculate the diffusion coefficient
 for a specified temperature, or make the corresponding Arrhenius plot of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln D$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

, 3) given the diffusion coefficient at one temperature and the activation
 energy, predict the diffusion coefficient at another temperature, or 4)
 given diffusion coefficients at two temperatures, be able to extract pre-expone
ntial factor and activation energy, plus predict the diffusion coefficient
 at an intermediate temperature.
 All of these tasks are quite straightforward once we recognize that taking
 the logarithm of both sides of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:BasicDiff-1"

\end_inset

 results in the formula of a line, as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffArrhenius"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln D=\ln D_{o}+(\frac{-Q}{R})T^{-1}=b+mx\label{eq:DiffArrhenius}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the axes are 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\ln D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=T^{-1},$
\end_inset

 the slope is 
\begin_inset Formula $m=-Q/R$
\end_inset

 and the intercept is 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\ln D_{o}$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, the slope is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffArrhSlope"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m=\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}=\frac{\ln D(T_{2})-\ln D(T_{1})}{T_{2}^{-1}-T_{1}^{-1}}\label{eq:DiffArrhSlope}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These relationships are represented schematically in Figure A.
 It should be noted that diffusion data are more commonly plotted on base-10
 
\begin_inset Formula $\log D$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 plots, but it is easy enough to modify equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffArrhenius"

\end_inset

 to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DiffArrhenius-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\log D=\log D_{o}+(\frac{-Q}{2.303R})T^{-1}=b+mx\label{eq:DiffArrhenius-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Be certain not to make the mistake of plotting temperature in 
\begin_inset Formula $^{o}C$
\end_inset

! All diffusion plots employ temperature in degrees Kelvin.
\end_layout

