\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Changing from 1D expansion to 3D expansion.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SimmonsBalluffi2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Doing the math for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta V/V=\{[(L+\varDelta L)^{3}-L^{3}]/L^{3}\}$
\end_inset

 and dropping all terms involving 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varDelta L)^{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varDelta L)^{3}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta L$
\end_inset

 itself is quite small, we find equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SimmonsBalluffi1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\varDelta V}{V}\simeq\frac{3\varDelta L}{L}\simeq X_{v}+\beta X_{v}\label{eq:SimmonsBalluffi1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the first term on the right reflects the addition of planes owing
 to vacancy formation, and the second term takes into account the lattice
 contraction and/or expansion in proportion to the site fraction of vacancies
 being formed.
 But we can also argue equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SimmonsBalluffi2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{3\varDelta a}{a}=\beta X_{v}\label{eq:SimmonsBalluffi2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
that the contraction and/or expansion of lattice planes by X-ray diffraction
 is in proportion to the site fraction of vacancies.
 Subtracting equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SimmonsBalluffi2"

\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SimmonsBalluffi1"

\end_inset

 eliminates the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta X_{v}$
\end_inset

term (so we needn't concern ourselves with the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

) and yields the desired equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SimmonsBalluffi3"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{v}=3\left(\frac{\varDelta L}{L}-\frac{\varDelta a}{a}\right)\label{eq:SimmonsBalluffi3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation may seem simple enough, but careful examination reveals just
 how difficult (how de rigueur) this experiment was at the time.
 Simmons and Balluffi had to measure extremely small differences between
 two very small quantities as they changed with temperature.
 You can pull up the original references to examine the original data and
 plots, but a schematic representation is given in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SimmonsBalluffi3"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

