\begin_layout Standard
A first observation is that both quantities (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta L/L$
\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta a/a$
\end_inset

) increase significantly with temperature, much more than can be explained
 by the addition of vacancies, and that both are concave upward with temperature.
 In fact, both quantities are reflecting the fact that thermal expansion
 is occurring with increasing temperature.
 This might seem to be a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

deal-breaker
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at first, until you realize that thermal expansion should be reflected
 identically in both quantities (dilatometry, XRD).
 Therefore, as per equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SimmonsBalluffi3"

\end_inset

, any thermal expansion-induced changes will cancel out.
 A second observation is that up to an onset temperature (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{onset}$
\end_inset

) there is no apparent difference in the two quantities.
 Actually there should be a difference at every temperature (as long as
 the vacancy concentration is in thermal equilibrium) however, below 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{onset}$
\end_inset

 the vacancy concentration is simply too small to be registered, meaning
 that any difference will be undetectable within the experimental limits
 of the two measurement methods.
 Above 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{onset}$
\end_inset

, however, there is a noticeable difference between (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta L/L$
\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta a/a$
\end_inset

), whose value is precisely one-third the vacancy concentration.
 It is obvious that the vacancy concentration increase monotonically with
 temperature up to the melting point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the natural logarithm of both sides of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SiteFracVacs"

\end_inset

 we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacArrh"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln X_{v}=\frac{\varDelta S_{v}}{R}+(\frac{-\varDelta H_{v}}{R})T^{-1}=b+mx\label{eq:VacArrh}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This tells us that by plotting the Simmons-Balluffi-derived 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{v}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 temperature data on an Arrhenius plot of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln X_{v}$
\end_inset

 vs.
 inverse temperature, as shown schematically in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SimmonsBalluffiArrhenius"

\end_inset

, we can extract both the entropy of vacancy formation (from the y-axis
 intercept) and the enthalpy of formation (from the slope).
\end_layout

