\begin_layout Plain Layout
Vacancy Formation in fcc Metals
\end_layout

\end_inset

Some Important Numbers and a Useful Relationship Regarding Vacancy Formation
 in fcc Metals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have the ability to establish equilibrium vacancy concentrations
 in metals, we can derive useful relationships, for example between the
 enthalpies of vacancy formation and the melting points of fcc metals.
 It turns out experimentally that the equilibrium vacancy concentrations
 at the melting points of fcc metals are almost always in the range, 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-4}\apprle X_{V}(T_{m})\lesssim10^{-3}$
\end_inset

.
 Let's plug this range of values into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SiteFracVacs"

\end_inset

 and assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta S_{v}\approx2.3R$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(2.3R/R)\approx10.$
\end_inset

 This yields equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacsAtMeltPoint"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
10^{-4}-10^{-3}\approx10\exp\left(\frac{-\varDelta H_{v}}{RT_{m}}\right)\label{eq:VacsAtMeltPoint}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
from which it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $9.2RT_{m}\lesssim\varDelta H_{v}\lesssim11.5RT_{m}$
\end_inset

, or approximately equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:VacsAtMeltPointShortcut"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta H_{v}(fcc)\approx10RT_{m}\label{eq:VacsAtMeltPointShortcut}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This rough estimate can come in quite handy, for example when you know the
 melting point of an fcc metal, but lack a readily available measured value
 for the enthalpy of vacancy formation.
 In addition, knowing that vacancy concentrations of fcc metals are on the
 order of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-4}$
\end_inset

to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-3}$
\end_inset

at their melting points is also good to put to memory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Bauerle and Kohler Experiment
\end_layout

\end_inset

The Classic Bauerle and Kohler Experiment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have good evidence for the existence of point defects like vacancies,
 but is there evidence for their motion? We can certainly argue 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

yes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the basis of tracer diffusion experiments.
 However, this question was answered in another way by Bauerle and Kohler
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bauerle_quenched-lattice_1957"

\end_inset

.
 This experiment is a bit more difficult to describe, but following the
 development will pay dividends.
 Since the experiment involved the use of electrical resistivity measurements,
 we need to introduce what is referred to as Matthiessen's rule, given by
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Matthiessen"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho=\rho_{t}+\rho_{v}+\rho_{d}\label{eq:Matthiessen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the total resistivity of a metal is shown to be governed by several
 electron-scattering mechanisms, including thermal vibrations (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}$
\end_inset

), scattering by vacancies (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{v}$
\end_inset

), and scattering by other defects like dislocations (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{d}$
\end_inset

).
 Since the resistivity of metals tends to be quite low, Bauerle and Kohler
 employed wires (to enhance the 
\lang american
measurable
\lang english
 resistance, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho l/A$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is wire length and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is cross-sectional area).
 The experimental campaign is represented schematically in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BauerleKohler1"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

