\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Schematic of the Bauerle and Kohler experimental campaign.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:BauerleKohler1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A wire of fcc metal was heated to what we will refer to as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quench temperature
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{q}$
\end_inset

) in order to set the equilibrium vacancy concentration for that temperature.
 In two separate experiments, the wire was heated and held at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{q}$
\end_inset

 and then quenched to room temperature, freezing in the equilibrium vacancy
 concentration of the quench temperature, or 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{v}(T_{q})$
\end_inset

.
 After electrical measurement at room temperature, the same wire was heated
 and held at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{q}$
\end_inset

 and then slow-cooled to room temperature.
 This second process allows for vacancy annihilation to take place, such
 that the resulting vacancy concentration is negligibly small.
 By subtracting the wire's resistivity slow-cooled (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{sc}$
\end_inset

) from that quenched (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{q}$
\end_inset

), we find equation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta\rho=\rho_{q}-\rho_{sc}=(\rho_{t}+\rho_{v}+\rho_{d})-(\rho_{t}+\rho_{d})=\rho_{v}=\alpha X_{v}(T_{q})\label{eq:Matthiessen2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are assuming that there are no changes in the other defects (including
 dislocations) during quenching vs.
 slow cooling, and that the thermal contribution to resistivity will be
 the same, since both measurements are made at room temperature.
 The thermal and other defect contributions therefore cancel, leaving only
 the vacancy scattering contribution, which we can set equal to a constant
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

) times the vacancy concentration frozen-in from the quench temperature
 [
\begin_inset Formula $X_{v}(T_{q})$
\end_inset

], as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Matthiessen2"

\end_inset

.
 This gives us something proportional to the equilibrium vacancy concentration
 at only one quench temperature, so Bauerle and Kohler repeated the procedure
 in Figure at several other quench temperatures.
 They then plotted the natural logarithm of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta\rho(T_{q})$
\end_inset

 vs.
 the inverse of quench temperature in Arrhenius fashion, as shown schematically
 in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BauerleKohler2"

\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a constant that does not change with quench temperature, the slope of
 the plot should reflect only the activation energy for vacancy formation,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{v}$
\end_inset

, as shown in the Figure.
\end_layout

