\begin_layout Standard
The result obtained for fcc gold by Bauerle and Kohler was 
\begin_inset Formula $94.6kJ/mole$
\end_inset

 or 0.98 eV, in excellent agreement with later work of Simmons and Balluffi
 by dilatometry/XRD (
\begin_inset Formula $90.7kJ/mole$
\end_inset

 or 0.94 eV).
 We should stress that since the quench-resistivity method only yields a
 quantity that is proportional to the vacancy concentration as opposed to
 the vacancy concentration itself (as in the dilatometry/XRD work), it is
 impossible to extract information regarding the pre-exponential factor
 and underlying entropic term by quench-resistivity method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The real advantage of the Bauerle-Kohler method, however, is that in addition
 to the enthalpy of vacancy formation, the enthalpy of vacancy motion can
 also be determined.
 To appreciate how this is done, we have to resurrect an old equation for
 the relaxation of vacancies, namely equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AverageComp"

\end_inset

 repeated here:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\bar{c}}{c_{o}}=\frac{8}{\pi^{2}}\exp(-\frac{t}{\tau})\label{eq:AverageComp-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You will recall this as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diffusion out of a slab
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 equation that we also employed to describe vacancy relaxation to sinks
 such as dislocations or grain boundaries.
 It is valid when the average composition relaxes to below 80% of the initial
 composition.
 In the present situation (quench-resistivity measurements) we can modify
 this equation to equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AverageComp-2"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{X_{v}}=X_{vo}\frac{8}{\pi^{2}}\exp(-\frac{t}{\tau})\label{eq:AverageComp-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X_{v}}$
\end_inset

is the average vacancy concentration and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{vo}$
\end_inset

 is the quenched-in starting vacancy concentration.
 This, in turn, can be related to the quench-resistivity measurements by
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AverageComp-2-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta\rho=\alpha X_{vo}\frac{8}{\pi^{2}}\exp(-\frac{t}{\tau})\label{eq:AverageComp-2-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
having inserted the relationship from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Matthiessen2"

\end_inset

, namely that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta\rho=\alpha$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X_{v}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is where the process of obtaining the motion enthalpy of vacancies
 gets a little complicated, so stay with me.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BauerleKohler3"

\end_inset

 shows a schematic of the temperature-time history of the series of experiments.
\end_layout

