\begin_layout Standard
Bauerle and Kohler began by setting a high initial concentration of quenched-in
 vacancies, by quenching from 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{q}$
\end_inset

 to room temperature, where the initial value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta\rho_{o}$
\end_inset

was measured.
 Remember that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta\rho$
\end_inset

 is always the as-quenched resistivity minus the slow-cooled resistivity.
 They then proceeded to take the wire to a relatively low intermediate temperatu
re, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{relax1}$
\end_inset

, high enough to facilitate vacancy relaxation to sinks, but not so high
 that a significant fraction of the residual vacancies are lost.
 This involved a series of sub-experiments: 1) heat at 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{relax1}$
\end_inset

 for a set time, 2) quench to room temperature, and 3) measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta\rho(t_{1})$
\end_inset

, and then repeat.
 As shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BauerleKohler3"

\end_inset

, the measured 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta\rho_{t}$
\end_inset

 is for the cumulative time, e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $t=t_{1}+t_{2}+t_{3}+etc.$
\end_inset

, at the relaxation temperature.
 They then went to a higher relaxation temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{relax2}$
\end_inset

, and repeated the same series of heat-quench-measure procedures.
 By taking the natural logarithm of both sides of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AverageComp-2-1"

\end_inset

, noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{vo}$
