reference "fig:MSC1"

\end_inset

.
 An easy way to recall this shorthand scheme is by remembering it as the
 M, S and C in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Materials SCience.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

M
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 stands for matter, or the lack thereof (for example a vacancy).
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

S
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 stands for the site on which the defect sits.
 And the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

C
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 stands for charge.
 However, in K-V notation the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

C
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

