\begin_inset Formula $Zr^{4+}O_{2}^{2-}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we can write the host cation species as 
\begin_inset Formula $(Zr_{Zr^{4+}}^{4+})^{x}$
\end_inset

, where the superscript 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

x
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 represents a neutral species insofar as effective charge is concerned.
 That is, the perfect (non-defective) crystal is charge-neutral.
 What we have written is that a 
\begin_inset Formula $Zr^{4+}$
\end_inset

 cation on a host 
\begin_inset Formula $Zr^{4+}$
\end_inset

site has an effective charge of zero (represented by the superscript 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

x
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in K-V notation.
 Similarly, we can write the host anion species as 
\begin_inset Formula $(O_{O^{2-}}^{2-})^{x}$
\end_inset

, representing an 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{2-}$
\end_inset

 host anion on an 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{2-}$
\end_inset

 site, with neutral effective charge.
 For a while we will continue to write host and defect species with real
 charge inside the parentheses, however this practice not part of the K-V
 system, but only a temporary 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

crutch
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to help get us comfortable with the notation scheme.
 In K-V notation, the host species we have thus far considered would be,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Zr_{Zr}^{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{O}^{x}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But what about point defects? Let's first consider oxygen defects, both
 vacancies and interstitials.
 Oxygen vacancies could be written as, 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{O^{2-}}^{0-})^{\text{â€¢â€¢}}$
\end_inset

, representing a vacancy with zero real charge on an oxygen 2- site.
 The effective charge is thus +2, represented by the double-dots.
 Another way to think about this is to begin with a charge-neutral occupied
 oxygen site and remove from it (and the perfect crystal) an 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{2-}$
\end_inset

species.
 Since the crystal began electrically neutral, what remains must be doubly-charg
ed positive.
 How about oxygen interstitials? Remember that, as opposed to close-packed
 metals where self-interstitials are energetically unfavorable, self-interstitia
ls of cations or anions in ionic crystals are quite possible so long as
