\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-stoichiometric Point Defect Reactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can divide non-stoichiometric point defect reactions into two categories,
 namely 1) those that decrease the O:M ratio, otherwise known as reduction
 reactions, and 2) those that increase the O:M ratio, otherwise known as
 oxidation reactions.
 As we will show, the former always produce electrons for charge-compensation
 and are n-type in nature, whereas the latter always produce electron hole
 for charge-compensation and are p-type in nature.
 Let's first consider reduction/n-type point defect reactions.
 Since oxygen gas either is produced (reduction reactions) or consumed (oxidatio
n reactions) and this can only take place at surfaces, all non-stoichiometric
 point defect reactions are inhomogeneous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can decrease the O:M ratio by either decreasing the oxygen content or
 by increasing the cation content.
 Both are accomplished by the removal of oxygen, resulting in oxygen gas
 being released, plus the simultaneous production of electrons.
 The oxygen-decreasing reaction, otherwise referred to as an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

oxygen deficit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reaction, results in the formation of oxygen vacancies, as per equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OxDeficit"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
O_{O}^{x}\stackrel{MO}{\rightleftarrows}\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}+V_{O}^{\text{â€¢â€¢}}+2e^{'}\label{eq:OxDeficit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is probably unnecessary at this point, but to keep you in the practice
 of checking off the 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{S}^{C}$
\end_inset

 rules, it can be seen that 1) there is one oxygen species on each side
 of the equation, 2) both sides are charge-neutral, and 3) we started with
 one anion site and end up with one anion site such that site-ratio is preserved.
 This is a balanced K-V reaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also decrease the O:M ratio by increasing the cation content.
 The cation-increasing reaction, otherwise referred to as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

metal-excess
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reaction results in the formation of metal interstitials, as per equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CatExcess"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{M}^{x}+O_{O}^{x}\stackrel{MO}{\rightleftarrows}\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}+M_{i}^{â€¢â€¢}+2e^{'}\label{eq:CatExcess}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I will leave it to you to check and see whether or not this equation satisfies
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{S}^{C}$
\end_inset

 rules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can increase the O:M ratio by either increasing the oxygen content or
 by decreasing the cation content.
 Both are accomplished by the addition of oxygen and the simultaneous production
 of electron holes.
 The oxygen-increasing reaction, otherwise referred to as an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

oxygen excess
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reaction, results in the formation of oxygen interstitials, as per equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:OxExcess"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}\stackrel{MO}{\rightleftarrows}O_{i}^{''}+2h^{\text{â€¢}}\label{eq:OxExcess}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be stressed that this equation is universal in oxides, meaning
 that the O:M ratio of the host (above the arrow in the equation) does not
 matter; the same reaction is as true in 
\begin_inset Formula $Li_{2}O$
\end_inset

 as it is in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{2}O_{5}$
\end_inset

.
 The cation-decreasing reaction, known otherwise as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cation deficit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reaction, results in the formation of cation vacancies, as per equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CatDeficit"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}\stackrel{MO}{\rightleftarrows}O_{O}^{x}+V_{M}^{''}+2h^{\text{â€¢}}\label{eq:CatDeficit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We must be careful, however, since this reaction is not universal but rather
 depends upon the O:M ratio of the host.
 For example, the corresponding cation deficit reaction for 
\begin_inset Formula $Al_{2}O_{3}$
\end_inset

would be given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AluminaCatDeficit"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{3}{2}\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}\stackrel{Al_{2}O_{3}}{\rightleftarrows}3O_{O}^{x}+2V_{Al}^{'''}+6h^{\text{â€¢}}\label{eq:AluminaCatDeficit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we are producing both anion sites and cation sites, but in the
 requisite 3:2 ratio for 
\begin_inset Formula $Al_{2}O_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aliovalent Doping Reactions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider how the oxide, MO, might be aliovalently-doped.
 Isovalent doping would be doping MO with oxide NO, where the valence state
 of the species N is 2+, as it is in the MO host.
 Aliovalent doping means doping with oxides having cations of different
 prevailing valence states than the host.
 We can write reactions for donor-doping, where the doping cation has a
 higher valence state than 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{2+},$
\end_inset

 and for acceptor-doping, where the doping cation has a lower valence state
 than 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{2+}$
\end_inset

.
 In each case we can charge-compensate with ionic point defects or with
 electronic defects.
 For example, let's consider donor-doping of MO with the trivalent cation
 N, or 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}O_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The ionic compensation reaction involves the formation of cation vacancies,
 as per equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DonorIonic"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{2}O_{3}\xrightarrow{MO}3O_{O}^{x}+2N_{M}^{\text{â€¢}}+V_{M}^{''}\label{eq:DonorIonic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a good reaction on which to test your K-V balancing skills.
 The reaction is obviously mass-balanced and charge-balanced, but what about
 site-ratio? Well, the reaction yields 3 anion sites and 3 cation sites,
 which are created in precisely the O:M ratio of the host (3:3 equals 1:1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The alternative to ionic compensation is electronic compensation.
 Note that in so doing, we need to release some of the oxygen as gas to
 maintain the M:O ratio of the host.
 The resulting reaction is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DonorElectronic"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{2}O_{3}\xrightarrow{MO}2O_{O}^{x}+2N_{M}^{\text{â€¢}}+2e^{'}+\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}\label{eq:DonorElectronic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's consider acceptor-doping of MO with the monovalent cation N, or
 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}O$
\end_inset

 for which the valence states are 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}^{+}O^{2-}$
\end_inset

.
 The ionic compensation reaction involves the formation of oxygen vacancies,
 as per equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AcceptorIonic"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{2}O\xrightarrow{MO}O_{O}^{x}+2N_{M}^{\text{'}}+V_{o}^{â€¢â€¢}\label{eq:AcceptorIonic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electronic compensation reaction requires the addition of some oxygen
 on the left side of the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:AcceptorElectronic"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{2}O+\frac{1}{2}\mathrm{O_{2}(g)}\xrightarrow{MO}2O_{O}^{x}+2N_{M}^{\text{'}}+2h^{â€¢}\label{eq:AcceptorElectronic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An obvious question to ask is which compensation mechanism (ionic, electronic)
 will take place in a certain dopant oxide/host oxide combination? The answer
 is that it depends upon the defect formation energetics, which we consider
 in the following section.
 You may also have missed a critical changeover from the previous two sections
 on stoichiometric and non-stoichiometric reactions to the present one on
 aliovalent doping reactions.
 You will notice forward and reverse arrows in the reactions of the prior
 two sections, but only a forward arrow in the reactions of the present
 section.
 This is owing to the fact that the first two sections dealt with equilibrium
 point defect reactions, meaning that the forward and reverse arrows were
 balanced.
 With aliovalent doping of ceramics, this is not the case, unless one has
 excess dopant oxide present at high temperature, namely a two-phase mixture.
 Instead, ceramics are donor-doped and acceptor-doped by incorporating a
 fixed amount of aliovalent dopant in the initial processing of the doped
 host ceramic.
 It is expected that the forward reaction goes to completion during processing
 at elevated temperature.
 Therefore, there is only a forward arrow.
 In other words, in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DonorIonic"

\end_inset

 for example, we can set the vacancy concentration equal to one-half the
 trivalent donor concentration, or 
\begin_inset Formula $[V_{M}^{''}]=\frac{1}{2}[N_{M}^{\text{â€¢}}].$
\end_inset

 It should be quite clear that all doping reactions, whether isovalent or
 aliovalent are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extrinsic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 reactions, since the dopant species comes from 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

outside
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the host crystal.
 It should also be clear that all doping reactions are inhomogeneous, reflecting
 the fact that dopants react with the surfaces of host oxide crystals/particles
 and undergo what is referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solid state reaction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (and long range diffusion) to achieve doping uniformity throughout the
 doped ceramic.
\end_layout

