\begin_layout Standard
We can approach the thermodynamics of point defect reactions in ionic solids/cer
amics in the same way we dealt with vacancy formation in metals.
 For example, for the formation of Schottky pairs in the oxide MO the reaction
 is repeated in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Schottky1-3"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
null\stackrel{MO}{\rightleftarrows}V_{M}^{\text{''}}+V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}\label{eq:Schottky1-3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only difference is that we cannot consider the formation of individual
 cation vacancies or oxygen vacancies.
 Given their charge, their formation would be highly unfavorable energetically.
 Instead, we form pairs consisting of a cation vacancy and an anion vacancy
 to maintain electroneutrality of the crystal, as per equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Schottky1-3"

\end_inset

.
 The enthalpy of this reaction can be written as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SchottkyH"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta H=X_{S}\varDelta H_{S}\label{eq:SchottkyH}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{S}$
\end_inset

 is the site fraction of Schottky pairs, namely the site fraction of each
 kind of vacancy on its sublattice, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta H_{S}$
\end_inset

 is the enthalpy per mole of Schottky pairs.
 The entropy of Schottky pair formation can be written as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SchottkyS"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\varDelta S=X_{S}\varDelta S_{S}-R[(X_{M}\ln X_{M}+(1-X_{M})\ln(1-X_{M}))+(X_{O}\ln X_{O}+(1-X_{O})\ln(1-X_{O}))]\label{eq:SchottkyS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta S_{S}$
\end_inset

 represents the non-configurational entropy of Schottky pair formation (per
 mole of Schottky pairs) and the term inside the brackets represents the
 configurational entropy.
 If we plot the two functions in equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SchottkyH"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SchottkyS"

\end_inset

 vs.
 the site fraction of Schottky pairs, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{S}$
\end_inset

, and recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta G=\varDelta H-T\varDelta S$
\end_inset

, we obtain the curves in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:DeltaGSchottky"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

