\begin_layout Standard
In 1954, G.
 Brouwer introduced what are now referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Brouwer diagrams
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Phillips Res.
 Rep., 9, 366).
 Brouwer diagrams are logarithmic plots of defect populations 1) vs.
 temperature (or rather inverse temperature), 2) vs.
 oxygen partial pressure, or 3) vs.
 dopant concentration, again on a logarithmic scale.
 We consider schematic versions for each of these in the following sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Brouwer Diagrams of Defect Concentration vs.
 Inverse Temperature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This type of diagram is useful for determining the energetics of point defect
 formation and motion in ionic solids/ceramics.
 For example, consider the extrinsic doping of NaCl by 
\begin_inset Formula $CaCl_{2}$
\end_inset

, where Ca is divalent (
\begin_inset Formula $Ca^{2+}Cl_{2}^{-}$
\end_inset

), as given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CaCl2dopingNaCl"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CaCl_{2}\xrightarrow{NaCl}Ca_{Na}^{\text{â€¢}}+2Cl_{Cl}^{x}+V_{Na}^{'}\label{eq:CaCl2dopingNaCl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note the use of the forward arrow only, connoting that this reaction goes
 to completion during the initial processing of the Ca-doped NaCl ceramic.
 Now consider the Schottky pair formation in NaCl, according to equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Schottky1-4"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
null\stackrel{NaCl}{\rightleftarrows}V_{Na}^{\text{'}}+V_{Cl}^{â€¢}\label{eq:Schottky1-4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

