for which the equilibrium expression is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SchottkyEq2-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K_{S}=[V_{Na}^{'}][V_{Cl}^{\text{â€¢}}]=\exp\left(\frac{\varDelta S_{S}}{R}\right)\exp\left(\frac{-\varDelta H_{S}}{RT}\right)\label{eq:SchottkyEq2-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step is to write what is commonly called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

electroneutrality condition,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which we will henceforth refer to as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ENC.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This condition is required to maintain the overall electroneutrality of
 the host crystal.
 The ENC is a straightforward expression setting the sum of all the negatively-c
harged point defects equal to the sum of all the positively-charged point
 defects, as per equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CaCl2inNaClENC"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[V_{Na}^{'}]=[Ca_{Na}^{\text{â€¢}}]+[V_{Cl}^{\text{â€¢}}]\label{eq:CaCl2inNaClENC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next step is to make so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Brouwer approximations.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 These are regimes in which two species--one positively charged and one
 negatively charged--predominate.
 As we consider equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CaCl2inNaClENC"

\end_inset

, it is clear that there should be two such regimes: 1) one where the Na-vacancy
 concentration is set by the Ca-donor doping, or 
\begin_inset Formula $[V_{Na}^{'}]=[Ca_{Na}^{\text{â€¢}}]$
\end_inset

, and 2) one where the Na-vacancy concentration is determined by the Schottky
 equilibrium with Cl-vacancies, or 
\begin_inset Formula $[V_{Na}^{'}]=[V_{Cl}^{\text{â€¢}}]$
\end_inset

.
 But which regime will be on the left and which will be on the right on
 a log [defect] vs.
 inverse temperature plot? Since temperature increases from right to left
 on plot with an inverse temperature (1/T) x-axis, it makes sense that the
 extrinsic, donor-doped regime would dominate at low temperatures, or to
