\begin_layout Section
Electrical Conductivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The usefulness and predictive power of schematic Brouwer diagrams can best
 be illustrated by considering electrical conductivity, which is controlled
 by the point defect species with the highest product of concentration and
 mobility.
 It turns out that there can be contributions from first, electronic species
 (electrons and electron holes), and from second, mobile ionic species.
 The former determines the electronic conductivity of a solid and the second
 determines the ionic conductivity of that solid.
 Together, these two contributions determine the overall electrical conductivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electronic Conductivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From introductory materials science and engineering courses, you should
 be familiar with the following equation for the electronic conductivity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma=ne\mu_{e}+pe\mu_{h}\label{eq:CondElectronic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the unit of electron charge, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{e}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{h}$
\end_inset

 are the mobilities of electrons and holes, respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are their concentrations, as previously defined.
 Usually, however, one species will dominate (as a majority species) whereas
 the other will have negligible concentration (a minority species).
 For example, electrons are majority species in the n-type semiconducting
 oxide MO, as reflected in the Brouwer diagram of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:MOredPox"

\end_inset

.
 In this case, the electronic conductivity reduces to equation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma=ne\mu_{e}\label{eq:CondElectronic-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is useful to do a unit analysis on the parameters in this equation to
 understand common usage in the materials community.
 The basic unit of conductivity is a Sieman per centimeter, or S/cm.
 The Sieman is the same as a reciprocal ohm (
\begin_inset Formula $1/\Omega$
\end_inset

), and according to Ohm's law an ohm is voltage/current (V/I) or a Joule
 per coulomb (J/C) divided by a coulomb per second (C/s), such that an ohm
 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{(J\text{\cdot\ensuremath{s)/C^{2}}}}$
\end_inset

.
 Placing these values into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CondElectronic-1"

\end_inset

, we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:ElectronicUnits"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{]\frac{C^{2}}{(J\text{\cdot}s\text{\cdot}cm)}=\frac{\#}{cm^{3}}C\mu_{e}}\label{eq:ElectronicUnits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that the basic units for mobility are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{cm^{2}}$
\end_inset

 per V
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

s (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{cm^{2}/V\text{\cdot}s}$
\end_inset

).
 This may make more sense written as a centimeter per second (carrier velocity)
 per volt per centimeter (driving force), or 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathrm{cm/s)/(V/cm})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is where the predictive power of schematic Brouwer diagrams comes in
