\begin_layout Standard
In the 1970s, the Ford Motor company developed a resistance-based oxygen
 sensor based upon such a 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\sigma$
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\log p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

behavior as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:MOredCond"

\end_inset

.
 Employing a highly pure titanium metal filament, which was subsequently
 oxidized to 
\begin_inset Formula $TiO_{2}$
\end_inset

, they achieved a reproducible conductance (the inverse of resistance, or
 G=1/R) vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{O_{2}}$
\end_inset

behavior that could be employed to monitor the oxygen content in the exhaust
 gases of the internal combustion engine.
 This enabled engineers to control the air-to-fuel ratio, otherwise known
