\begin_layout Subsection
Ionic Conductivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It makes sense that 
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ionic conductivity
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
ionic conductivity
\end_layout

\end_inset

 will likewise be determined by the product of ion concentration, ion charge,
 and ion mobility.
 A development of the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Nernst-Einstein
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 relationship is beyond the scope of the present text, but one form of it
 describes the ionic mobility of a charged species, as given in equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NernstEinsteinMob"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu_{i}=\frac{D_{i}q_{i}}{kT}\label{eq:NernstEinsteinMob}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the diffusivity of an ionic species of charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is absolute temperature and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is Boltzmann's constant.
 Since the product 
\begin_inset Formula $kT$
\end_inset

 is in units of Joules, the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{cm^{2}/s}$
\end_inset

 and C divided by Joules yields the appropriate units for mobility of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{cm^{2}}$
\end_inset

 per 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cdot s$
\end_inset

.
 The carrier concentration will be the concentration of mobile ions or 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\#/cm^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The charge of the mobile species is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

, which in turn is equal to the product of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 (the number of charges on a mobile ion, e.g., -2 in the case of oxygen ions)
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

, the unit of electron charge, or 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}=z_{i}e$
\end_inset

.
 Putting all this together, the product of carrier content, carrier charge,
 and carrier mobility is given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NerstEinsteinCond"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{i}=c_{i}q_{i}\left(\frac{D_{i}q_{i}}{kT}\right)=\left(\frac{c_{i}q_{i}^{2}}{kT}\right)D_{i}\label{eq:NerstEinsteinCond}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is yet another version of the Nernst-Einstein relationship.
 Let's apply this equation to the situation of calcia-doped zirconia, whose
 doping reaction is repeated here as equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CaDopedZrO2-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CaO\xrightarrow{MO}Ca_{Zr}^{''}+O_{O}^{x}+V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}\label{eq:CaDopedZrO2-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As always, the forward arrow indicates a reaction that goes to completion
 during the firing of calcia-doped zirconia.
 The resulting electroneutrality condition is 
\begin_inset Formula $[V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}]=[Ca_{Zr}^{''}]$
\end_inset

, as shown on the right side of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CSZPox"

\end_inset

.
 The formula unit for CaO-doped 
\begin_inset Formula $ZrO_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be written as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CSZFormUnit"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(ZrO_{2})_{1-x}(CaO\text{â–¡})_{x}=(Zr_{1-x}Ca_{x})O_{2-x}\text{â–¡}_{x}\label{eq:CSZFormUnit}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the box represents oxygen vacancies.
 In fact, we can write the ionic conductivity in terms of either oxygen
 diffusivity or oxygen vacancy diffusivity, as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:DblNernstEinstein"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{i}=\left(\frac{c_{O^{2-}}q_{O^{2-}}^{2}}{kT}\right)D_{O}=\left(\frac{c_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}q_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}^{2}}{kT}\right)D_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}\label{eq:DblNernstEinstein}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}$
\end_inset

 subscript refers to oxygen vacancies.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{O^{2-}}^{2}=(-2e)^{2}=q_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}^{2}=(+2e)^{2}$
\end_inset

, we can cancel these terms and also the 
\begin_inset Formula $kT$
\end_inset

 product from both sides to obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CSZcDprod"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c_{O^{2-}}D_{O}=c_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}D_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}\label{eq:CSZcDprod}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we divide both sides by the concentration of overall oxygen sites (
\begin_inset Formula $c_{OS}$
\end_inset

), and replace 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{O^{2-}}/c_{OS}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}/c_{OS}$
\end_inset

 by the respective site fractions, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{O}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}$
\end_inset

, respectively, we obtain equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CSZsiteFrac"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X_{O}D_{O}=X_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}D_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}\label{eq:CSZsiteFrac}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This may not look familiar, but we have previously dealt with a version
 of this equation when dealing with self diffusion by vacancy mechanism
 in metals.
 You can find it back in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SelfVacDiffComp"

\end_inset

, which can be rewritten as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{A}=X_{v}D_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 In reality, this expression should be 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}D_{A}=(1-X_{v})D_{A}=X_{v}D_{v}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case of metals, however, the site fraction of vacancies is negligibly
 small such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{A}=(1-X_{v})\approx1$
\end_inset

.
 However, in the case of CaO-doped 
\begin_inset Formula $ZrO_{2}$
\end_inset

 the sizable vacancy content cannot be ignored.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider zirconia doped by 15 mole percent of calcia.
 The formula unit can be written as in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CSZFormUnit-1"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(ZrO_{2})_{0.85}(CaO\text{â–¡})_{0.15}=(Zr_{0.85}Ca_{0.15})O_{1.85}\text{â–¡}_{0.15}\label{eq:CSZFormUnit-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that the site fractions will be 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{O}=1.85/2=0.925$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}=0.15/2=0.075$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the ratio of site fractions (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{O}/X_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}$
\end_inset

) is 12.33.
 From equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CSZsiteFrac"

\end_inset

 it follows that the vacancy diffusivity at every temperature will be 12.33
 times the oxygen ion diffusivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What we need to be able to do is to go back and forth between ionic conductivity
 and either of the diffusivities (oxygen, vacancy).
 If we know the concentration of overall oxygen sites, we can calculate
 the concentration of either occupied oxygen sites (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{O}c_{OS}$
\end_inset

) or of oxygen vacancies (
\begin_inset Formula $X_{V_{O}^{â€¢â€¢}}c_{OS}$
\end_inset

).
 The concentration of overall oxygen sites can be calculated in a couple
 of ways.
 The cubic fluorite structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $ZrO_{2}$
\end_inset

 is given in Figure 
